<section class="chapter" id="cmmi-c1">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter One</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">The Big Picture —<br>What Is CMMI?</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Before documenting anything meaningfully, you need to understand the problem CMMI was invented to solve, what the model actually is (and isn't), and why a company like our organization — already holding ISO 9001 and ISO 27001 — pursues it anyway.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">Origins at the SEI</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">What CMMI asserts</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">v2.0 and what came after</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">CMMI vs ISO</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Why our organization needs it</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">A Crisis Produces a Model</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Late 1980s: software projects are failing spectacularly — defence systems years late, millions over budget, or cancelled outright. The US Department of Defense asks Carnegie Mellon's Software Engineering Institute (SEI) a question that sounds simple: <em>what separates organisations that consistently deliver from those that don't?</em> After studying hundreds of organisations, the SEI's answer was uncomfortable for an industry that worshipped talent: the winners didn't merely have better people — they had <strong>repeatable, disciplined processes</strong>. Success wasn't a lucky accident; it was the output of a well-run system. That research became the Capability Maturity Model (1991), which evolved into CMMI — the <em>Integration</em> marking the merger of separate models for software, systems engineering and acquisition.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Quick fact</div>
 CMMI is stewarded today by ISACA (which absorbed the CMMI Institute, itself spun out of Carnegie Mellon). Over 10,000 organisations across 100+ countries have been appraised. our organization works with <strong>CMMI v3.0</strong> (2018); its successor <strong>CMMI V3.0</strong> arrived in 2023 with reorganised content and new domains — the core ideas in this booklet carry over intact, and the maturity-level ladder is unchanged.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">What the Model Actually Is</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">CMMI is a <strong>framework of best practices</strong> — a structured catalogue of the things high-performing engineering organisations consistently do. The recipe-book analogy holds: it specifies the outcomes ("plan your work", "trace your requirements", "review your peers' outputs", "learn from your defects") but never the tools, languages or methodologies. Scrum or waterfall, Jira or spreadsheets — CMMI is indifferent, so long as the practice happens, is owned by the organisation, and leaves evidence.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">Equally important is what CMMI is <em>not</em>. It is not a quality stamp on a product (it appraises the <em>organisation's process</em>), not a one-time certificate (ratings expire — which is why our organization recertifies), and not a documentation contest (documents are evidence of the system, never the point of it).</p>

 <div class="pull-quote fade-up"><p>"CMMI is not about bureaucracy. It's about building an organisation where good outcomes are the result of good systems — not just good luck."</p></div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Why Organisations Pursue It — and Why our organization Does</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Two honest reasons. <strong>Internal:</strong> the journey forces an organisation to confront how it actually works — gaps surface, processes get written down, teams get disciplined, and tribal knowledge becomes institutional knowledge that survives any individual resignation. <strong>External:</strong> the rating is a procurement trust signal. Government buyers and international funders shortlist on it. For our organization — delivering national-scale government systems, donor-funded education platforms and identity-management infrastructure — CMMI L3 is not a nice-to-have; it is a tender qualification, the engineering counterpart to what SOC 2 does for security trust (see Part I of the SOC 2 booklet for that story).</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">CMMI Next to ISO 9001 and ISO 27001</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">our organization holds all three, and they are lenses, not duplicates:</p>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Framework</th><th>Focus</th><th>The question it asks</th><th>Relationship</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>ISO 9001</td><td>Quality management</td><td>"Does a quality system consistently meet customer requirements?"</td><td>Broad quality lens; CMMI digs far deeper into engineering and delivery.</td></tr>
 <tr><td>ISO 27001</td><td>Information security</td><td>"Are information assets protected?"</td><td>Security-specific; complementary, almost no overlap.</td></tr>
 <tr><td>CMMI</td><td>Engineering &amp; delivery maturity</td><td>"Are development and delivery processes mature, repeatable, improving?"</td><td>The deepest dive into how software is estimated, built, tested, managed.</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>
 <p class="fade-up">The practical synergy matters for the documentation team: one well-designed artifact frequently serves two masters. A risk register feeds ISO 9001 clause 6 <em>and</em> CMMI's RSK practice area; a corrective-action log feeds ISO nonconformity handling <em>and</em> CMMI's CAR. Designing documents once, for all frameworks, is the cheapest compliance strategy our organization has.</p>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Take Away — Chapter 1</div>
 <ol>
 <li>CMMI encodes decades of evidence that repeatable process — not heroics — produces reliable delivery.</li>
 <li>It prescribes outcomes, never tools or methods; agile teams qualify as readily as waterfall ones.</li>
 <li>For our organization, L3 is a commercial qualification for government and donor-funded work.</li>
 <li>CMMI, ISO 9001 and ISO 27001 are complementary lenses — design artifacts that serve all three at once.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ CMMI CH 2 ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="cmmi-c2">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Two</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">The Five Maturity Levels —<br>A Ladder, Not a Switch</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The maturity level is the single number the outside world sees, so it's worth understanding precisely what each level claims — and what changed inside our organization when it climbed from project-level discipline to organisation-wide process ownership.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">ML1 → ML5</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">The L2 → L3 shift</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">What "Defined" means</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Why levels can't be skipped</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Climbing One Rung at a Time</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Maturity is cumulative: each level requires every rung below it to be solid. An appraisal targeting Level 3 examines Level 2 practices too — you cannot decorate chaos with org-wide standards and call it Defined. The five rungs:</p>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Name</th><th>Core idea</th><th>Process owner</th><th>our organization status</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>ML 1</td><td>Initial</td><td>Heroic individuals save the day — every time</td><td>Nobody / the hero</td><td>The starting point, long past</td></tr>
 <tr><td>ML 2</td><td>Managed</td><td>Projects are planned, tracked, disciplined — individually</td><td>Each project team</td><td>Prerequisite, satisfied</td></tr>
 <tr><td>ML 3</td><td>Defined</td><td>The organisation owns standard processes; projects tailor them</td><td>The organisation</td><td><strong>Current certified level ★</strong></td></tr>
 <tr><td>ML 4</td><td>Quantitatively Managed</td><td>Statistical control of process performance</td><td>Data systems + management</td><td>Not currently pursued</td></tr>
 <tr><td>ML 5</td><td>Optimising</td><td>Continuous, data-driven innovation on the process itself</td><td>Whole-organisation culture</td><td>Not currently pursued</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">A V3.0 note on Level 2</div><p>In CMMI <strong>V3.0</strong>, Maturity Level 2 was redefined as <em>all</em> Practice Areas operating at Capability Level 2 &mdash; not only the project-management ones. For an organisation like our organization this only reinforces the cumulative ladder below: every Practice Area must be addressed on the way up, with no skipping rungs.</p></div>

 <p class="fade-up"><strong>Level 1</strong> isn't an insult — every organisation starts there. Work gets done, sometimes brilliantly, but success depends on specific individuals; remove the hero and the project collapses. The business risk isn't incompetence, it's <em>fragility</em>. <strong>Level 2</strong> brings discipline to each project: plans exist, requirements are managed, progress is tracked. But the discipline is local — two projects in the same building may run completely differently, and every new project reinvents its own wheel.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Level 3 Shift — The Organisation Takes Ownership</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Level 3 is a change of <em>owner</em>, not just of effort. A set of <strong>standard organisational processes</strong> is defined, documented and maintained centrally in the Process Asset Library; every project starts from those standards and <strong>tailors</strong> them — with documented rationale — to its context. Lessons flow back: post-project reviews update the standards, so the organisation literally learns. The exam question changes accordingly:</p>
 <div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The key distinction</div>
 Level 2 asks: <em>"Does this project have a process?"</em> &nbsp;Level 3 asks: <em>"Does the organisation have a standard process that this project used and adapted?"</em> The first is about effort; the second is about institutional memory.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">What "Defined" Actually Requires</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">A process counts as defined only when it is <strong>written</strong> clearly enough for a competent stranger to follow; <strong>stored</strong> centrally and accessibly (the PAL); <strong>owned</strong> — someone is responsible for maintaining it; <strong>used</strong> on real projects, with evidence of that use; and <strong>tailorable</strong>, with guidance on permitted adaptations. The corollary the documentation team lives by: a beautiful process document nobody opens fails the definition on the "used" clause — appraisers check usage, not prose.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the same event at three maturity levels</div>
 A key developer resigns mid-project. <strong>ML1:</strong> the project stalls; nobody else knows how the deployment works; the client finds out the hard way. <strong>ML2:</strong> the project's own documentation softens the blow, but the sister project that loses its developer next month has no such luck — its discipline was different. <strong>ML3 (our organization today):</strong> the standard onboarding process, the project's tailored plan, the configuration management records and the peer-review trail mean a replacement is productive in days — and the post-project review notes what could make it faster still. Same event, three different companies.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Levels 4 and 5 — The View Upstairs</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">At <strong>ML4</strong> the organisation puts statistical control around its processes — predicting defect rates and schedule variance from historical baselines, and knowing when a deviation is noise versus signal. <strong>ML5</strong> turns that machinery on the processes themselves: continuous, measured innovation. These levels are rare, expensive, and typical of aerospace and defence primes. For our organization the practical relevance is directional: the measurement habits built at L3 (estimation data, defect data, review metrics) are exactly the raw material an eventual L4 ambition would need.</p>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Take Away — Chapter 2</div>
 <ol>
 <li>Maturity is sequential; an L3 appraisal inspects L2 practices too.</li>
 <li>L2 → L3 moves process ownership from individual projects to the organisation.</li>
 <li>"Defined" = written + central + owned + <em>used</em> + tailorable. Usage evidence is non-negotiable.</li>
 <li>The measurement habits of a healthy L3 are the seed of any future L4 ambition.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ CMMI CH 3 ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="cmmi-c3">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Three</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Anatomy of the Model —<br>How CMMI v3.0 Is Built</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Most people meet CMMI as a wall of acronyms. This chapter gives you the map: how the model is organised, what's inside a Practice Area, what practice "levels" mean, and how the pieces combine into a maturity rating. Once you see the architecture, the other chapters become easy.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">4 categories</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">20 Practice Areas</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Inside a PA</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Practice levels 1–3</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">How rating works</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Four Questions, Four Categories</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">CMMI v3.0 organises its guidance into <strong>20 Practice Areas (PAs)</strong>, grouped into four categories — each answering one fundamental question about an organisation:</p>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Category</th><th>The question</th><th>PAs</th><th>Flavour</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td><strong>Doing</strong></td><td>How do we actually build the product?</td><td>8 — RDM, TS, PI, VV, PR, CM, PQA, SAM</td><td>Engineering &amp; technical discipline</td></tr>
 <tr><td><strong>Managing</strong></td><td>How do we plan, track and steer the work?</td><td>5 — EST, PLAN, MC, RSK, IRP</td><td>Project &amp; programme management</td></tr>
 <tr><td><strong>Enabling</strong></td><td>What supports the people doing the work?</td><td>4 — DAR, OT, PAD, CAR</td><td>Decisions, training, assets, root cause</td></tr>
 <tr><td><strong>Improving</strong></td><td>How does the organisation itself get better?</td><td>3 — PCM, GOV, II</td><td>Governance &amp; the improvement engine</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What&rsquo;s new in CMMI V3.0 (released 2023)</div><p>The four categories and the core Development Practice Areas above are what our Level 3 rests on &mdash; and they carry over from V2.0 largely unchanged. What <strong>V3.0</strong> added: <strong>new optional Practice Areas</strong> &mdash; Data Management (DM), Data Quality (DQ), Enabling Safety (ESAF), Enabling Security (ESEC), Enabling Virtual Work (EVW), Managing Security Threats &amp; Vulnerabilities (MST) and Workforce Empowerment (WE); <strong>new domains</strong> (Data, People and Virtual) alongside Development, Services, Suppliers, Safety and Security; and refreshed content for <strong>DevSecOps and Agile</strong>. The biggest conceptual shift: <strong>Maturity Level 2 is now defined as every Practice Area at Capability Level 2</strong> &mdash; process maturity is treated as improving all processes in parallel, rather than mastering a project-management foundation first.</p></div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Inside a Practice Area</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Every PA has the same skeleton, and knowing it changes how you read the model. Each PA states an <strong>intent</strong> (what outcome this area exists to produce), a <strong>value</strong> statement (why the business should care), and a set of <strong>practices</strong> — the individual, checkable behaviours. Practices are numbered by level: <code>RSK 2.1</code> means Risk &amp; Opportunity Management, practice level 2, first practice. This is the unit the appraisal team actually characterises: not "is our organization good at risk?", but "is practice RSK 2.2 fully implemented across the sampled projects?"</p>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>Practice levels</strong> describe the sophistication of implementation. Level 1 practices are the basic "do the thing at all" versions. Level 2 practices add project-level discipline — planned, resourced, tracked. Level 3 practices add the organisational dimension: the project uses the <em>org-standard</em> process, tailored, and contributes data and lessons back. A Level 3 rating requires the level 1, 2 <em>and</em> 3 practices of the in-scope PAs to be satisfied — which is the formal version of "the ladder's lower rungs must hold".</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Worked example — one practice, three levels</div>
 Take estimation. <strong>EST level 1:</strong> someone produces an estimate before work starts. <strong>Level 2:</strong> the project estimates using a documented method, records assumptions, and re-estimates when scope changes. <strong>Level 3:</strong> the project estimates using <em>our organization's standard estimation process</em>, calibrated with historical data from past projects, and feeds its own actuals back into the organisational dataset. Same activity, deepening institutionalisation — that gradient is the entire model in miniature.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">How 20 PAs Become One Number</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">During the appraisal each practice, in each sampled project, is characterised — Fully / Largely / Partially / Not Implemented (Chapter 7 details the mechanics). The Lead Appraiser aggregates: weaknesses in a practice across projects pull the PA down; any in-scope PA failing its goals caps the maturity level. There is no partial credit at the headline level — no "L3 except for training". That all-or-nothing aggregation explains the documentation team's golden priority: <em>consistency beats brilliance</em>. One exemplary project cannot compensate for a sister project that skipped peer reviews; the weakest sampled project sets the ceiling.</p>

 <div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Reading the model without drowning</div>
 You do not need to memorise 20 intents and ~80 practices. The the documentation team's working method: know the four categories cold; know which artifacts our organization produces for each PA (Chapters 4–6 give you the tables); and when a question gets specific, open the model and read the two pages for that PA. CMMI is a reference book, not a novel.</div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Take Away — Chapter 3</div>
 <ol>
 <li>The model = 4 categories → 20 Practice Areas → individual numbered practices. Practices are what gets judged.</li>
 <li>Practice levels 1→3 encode deepening institutionalisation: done → disciplined → organisational.</li>
 <li>The rating aggregates with no partial credit — the weakest sampled project sets the ceiling.</li>
 <li>Treat the model as a reference book; this booklet's PA tables are your everyday index.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ CMMI CH 4 ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="cmmi-c4">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Four</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Doing —<br>Building the Product Right</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Eight Practice Areas cover the engineering core: from capturing what the client actually needs, through design, integration and testing, to managing versions, assuring process quality and handling suppliers. For each, this chapter gives the idea, what good looks like at L3, and the artifacts the documentation team should expect to file.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">RDM</span><span class="topic-pill">TS</span><span class="topic-pill">PI</span><span class="topic-pill">VV</span><span class="topic-pill">PR</span><span class="topic-pill">CM</span><span class="topic-pill">PQA</span><span class="topic-pill">SAM</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Engineering Chain</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">The first four PAs form a chain that mirrors a project's life. <strong>RDM (Requirements Development &amp; Management)</strong> turns client needs into written, traceable requirements and controls every change to them — the traceability matrix is its signature artifact, linking each requirement forward to design, code and tests. <strong>TS (Technical Solution)</strong> covers design: alternatives considered, decisions recorded with rationale, architecture reviewed against the org standard. <strong>PI (Product Integration)</strong> plans how components assemble — integration sequence, interface agreements, environment readiness — so "it works on my machine" never becomes the integration strategy. <strong>VV (Verification &amp; Validation)</strong> closes the chain with the two questions every delivery must answer: did we build it <em>right</em> (verification, against spec) and did we build the <em>right thing</em> (validation, against client need)? Acceptance criteria are set before testing begins, not negotiated after.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the requirement that changed on a phone call</div>
 A ministry stakeholder calls a our organization project lead and asks for an extra field on a registration form. Tempting fix: just add it. The RDM-disciplined version costs thirty minutes more: log the change request, assess impact (the field touches the data model, two reports, and a privacy review), get client sign-off, update the traceability matrix, let VV update the test cases. Eight months later, when the appraiser asks "show me how requirement changes are controlled", that half hour <em>is</em> the answer. And when a different stakeholder asks why the field exists — the trail answers that too.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Guardrail PAs</h2>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>PR (Peer Reviews)</strong> institutionalises the cheapest defect-removal technique known: colleagues formally reviewing work products — code, designs, documents — before they're finalised, with findings recorded and tracked to closure. At L3 the review procedure is standardised and review data is collected for analysis (which feeds CAR, Chapter 6). <strong>CM (Configuration Management)</strong> guarantees you always know which version of what is where: identified configuration items, controlled changes, baselines, and periodic configuration audits. Git provides 80% of this for code automatically; the discipline is extending the same rigour to documents, environments and releases. <strong>PQA (Process Quality Assurance)</strong> is the internal referee: someone <em>independent of the project</em> checks that teams actually follow the standard processes, records non-conformances, and escalates what doesn't get fixed. <strong>SAM (Supplier Agreement Management)</strong> applies the same discipline to third parties — agreements from standard templates, deliverables accepted against criteria, supplier performance monitored. (Readers of the SOC 2 booklet will recognise the family resemblance to vendor risk management — one supplier file can serve both.)</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">What the Document Library — Doing PAs</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>PA</th><th>Signature artifacts</th><th>Typical weakness appraisers find</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>RDM</td><td>Requirements spec, traceability matrix, change requests with impact analysis &amp; approvals</td><td>Matrix exists but stops at design — no links to test cases</td></tr>
 <tr><td>TS</td><td>Design documents, architecture review minutes, decision records with alternatives</td><td>Decisions recorded without the rejected alternatives or rationale</td></tr>
 <tr><td>PI</td><td>Integration plan &amp; sequence, interface agreements, environment readiness checks</td><td>Integration "planned" verbally; only the final smoke test is documented</td></tr>
 <tr><td>VV</td><td>Test plans &amp; reports, UAT sign-offs, acceptance criteria agreed pre-test</td><td>Criteria written after testing, fitted to what passed</td></tr>
 <tr><td>PR</td><td>Review records with findings, closure tracking, review metrics</td><td>Reviews happen in pull requests but findings aren't summarised or analysed</td></tr>
 <tr><td>CM</td><td>Configuration plan, baseline records, change approvals, CM audit reports</td><td>Code versioned rigorously; documents and environments not at all</td></tr>
 <tr><td>PQA</td><td>QA audit schedule &amp; reports, non-conformance log, escalation records</td><td>The "independent" reviewer reports to the project manager being reviewed</td></tr>
 <tr><td>SAM</td><td>Supplier agreements, acceptance records, performance review notes</td><td>Contracts exist; monitoring against them doesn't</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: "Our agile workflow already does all this — nothing to document."</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">Mostly true on the first half: backlog refinement is RDM, definition-of-done is VV, pull requests are PR, pipelines are CM. The gap is recognition and recording — sprint artifacts must be <em>kept</em>, linked to the standard process they instantiate, and consistent across teams. Agile teams rarely lack practice; they lack the trail that proves it.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Take Away — Chapter 4</div>
 <ol>
 <li>RDM→TS→PI→VV is the engineering chain; traceability is the thread that holds it together.</li>
 <li>PR, CM, PQA and SAM are the guardrails — review, version, referee, and supplier discipline.</li>
 <li>Each PA has signature artifacts; the table above is the documentation team's filing checklist.</li>
 <li>Agile ceremonies generate most of this evidence naturally — capture it, link it, keep it.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ CMMI CH 5 ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="cmmi-c5">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Five</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Managing —<br>Steering the Work</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Five Practice Areas govern how work is sized, planned, tracked, de-risked and kept honest when reality misbehaves. This is where most appraisal interview time is spent, because every project member — not just managers — participates in these practices daily.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">EST</span><span class="topic-pill">PLAN</span><span class="topic-pill">MC</span><span class="topic-pill">RSK</span><span class="topic-pill">IRP</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">From Guess to Commitment</h2>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>EST (Estimating)</strong> demands that effort, cost and schedule estimates come from a documented method fed by historical data — not gut feel dressed in a spreadsheet. At L3 this is the most visibly "organisational" management PA: past projects' actuals live in a shared dataset, and new estimates are calibrated against them. Assumptions are recorded so that when scope shifts, the estimate's logic can shift with it. <strong>PLAN (Planning)</strong> turns the estimate into a commitment: scope, schedule, resources, stakeholders, data management and risk all in an org-standard plan template, reviewed and committed to by the people who must deliver it. The plan is then a living document — L3 planning is recognisable by its <em>revision history</em>.</p>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>MC (Monitor &amp; Control)</strong> keeps the plan honest: progress reviewed against milestones at a defined cadence, deviations surfaced early, corrective actions logged and tracked to closure. The cheap, powerful artifact is the status report with a consistent structure — milestone status, effort actuals vs plan, top risks, issues, decisions needed. Twelve of those in a folder demonstrate MC almost single-handedly.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the slipping milestone</div>
 Week 14 of a 30-week education-platform delivery: the data-migration workstream is ten days behind, visible in the weekly status review (MC). The project lead logs a corrective action — re-sequence UAT to start with modules not blocked by migration — and raises the risk register entry for "legacy data quality worse than assumed" from amber to red (RSK), with a mitigation: borrow a data engineer for two sprints. The client hears about it in that week's report, not at the deadline. At appraisal time this one episode, fully papered, demonstrates three PAs working as a system. Maturity isn't the absence of slippage — it's slippage <em>with headlights on</em>.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Risk, and What Happens Anyway</h2>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>RSK (Risk &amp; Opportunity Management)</strong> asks each project to identify what could go wrong (and right — opportunities are in scope too), score probability and impact, plan mitigations, and review the register at status meetings so it stays a living instrument rather than kickoff theatre. SOC 2 readers will recognise the machinery from the organisational risk register; RSK runs the same engine per project. <strong>IRP (Incident Resolution &amp; Prevention)</strong> handles what materialises anyway: incidents logged in a standard format, diagnosed to root cause for significant cases, resolved, and — the half teams forget — <em>prevented from recurring</em>, which is where IRP hands off to CAR (Chapter 6). A production incident on a government platform that produces a ticket, an RCA, a fix and a prevention action is IRP demonstrated end to end.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">What the Document Library — Managing PAs</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>PA</th><th>Signature artifacts</th><th>Typical weakness appraisers find</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>EST</td><td>Estimation worksheets with method &amp; assumptions, historical actuals dataset, re-estimates</td><td>A single number with no method, assumptions or recalibration</td></tr>
 <tr><td>PLAN</td><td>Project plan (org template), stakeholder commitments, revision history</td><td>Plan written for kickoff, never updated — a snapshot, not an instrument</td></tr>
 <tr><td>MC</td><td>Status reports on cadence, milestone reviews, corrective-action log</td><td>Status reported in meetings but never written; actions untracked</td></tr>
 <tr><td>RSK</td><td>Risk register with scores &amp; mitigations, review evidence in minutes</td><td>Register frozen since week one — every date the same</td></tr>
 <tr><td>IRP</td><td>Incident log, RCA reports, prevention actions, escalation records</td><td>Incidents fixed heroically in chat, leaving no trail and no prevention</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: managing the project in meetings and memory.</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">Interviews can confirm artifacts; they cannot replace them. A project lead who runs a tight ship verbally will sail through conversation and still sink the practice characterisation, because affirmations without artifacts cap at "partially implemented". The fix costs minutes: write the status note, export the register, file the RCA.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Take Away — Chapter 5</div>
 <ol>
 <li>EST→PLAN→MC is the commitment pipeline: method-based estimate, committed living plan, tracked reality.</li>
 <li>RSK keeps the register alive per project; IRP turns incidents into prevention, not just fixes.</li>
 <li>Maturity is slippage with headlights on — deviations surfaced, papered, corrected.</li>
 <li>Verbal excellence caps at "partially implemented"; the written trail is what rates.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ CMMI CH 6 ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="cmmi-c6">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Six</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Enabling &amp; Improving —<br>The Seven PAs Everyone Underestimates</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Seven Practice Areas — four Enabling, three Improving — get a fraction of the attention the engineering PAs receive, yet they are where re-appraisals most often stumble and where Level 3 either lives or quietly dies. They are also, not coincidentally, the PAs where the documentation team does its most visible work.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">DAR</span><span class="topic-pill">OT</span><span class="topic-pill">PAD</span><span class="topic-pill">CAR</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">PCM</span><span class="topic-pill">GOV</span><span class="topic-pill">II</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Enabling — What Holds the Teams Up</h2>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>DAR (Decision Analysis &amp; Resolution)</strong> formalises how <em>significant</em> decisions get made: define criteria first, identify alternatives, evaluate against the criteria, record the choice and rationale. Not every decision — choosing a lunch vendor needs no matrix — but architecture selections, build-vs-buy calls, and platform choices do. The artifact is a decision record showing the losing options got a fair hearing; its quiet superpower is ending re-litigation, because the reasoning survives the meeting. <strong>OT (Organisational Training)</strong> is the PA behind the training matrix: organisational training needs identified, a plan to meet them, delivery records, and effectiveness checked. It is among the most commonly cited weaknesses in re-appraisals for one mundane reason — organisations train their people and forget to <em>record</em> it, especially for mid-cycle hires. <strong>PAD (Process Asset Development)</strong> builds and maintains the assets everything else depends on: the standard processes, templates, guidelines and examples in the PAL, plus the tailoring guidance projects use to adapt them. <strong>CAR (Causal Analysis &amp; Resolution)</strong> is organisational learning with teeth: take recurring defects or incidents (fed by PR review data and IRP logs), dig to root cause, fix the <em>cause</em>, and verify the fix changed the trend.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — CAR earning its keep</div>
 The quarterly review of peer-review data shows the same defect class — mishandled date formats — appearing in three projects. A CAR session traces the root cause: the shared utility library's documentation shows the deprecated function first. The fix is organisational, not project-level: update the library docs, add a lint rule, brief the teams, and watch the defect class vanish from the next quarter's review data. That closed loop — data → cause → systemic fix → verified trend — is the single most persuasive Level 3 behaviour an organisation can show an appraiser.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Improving — The Engine Room of Level 3</h2>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>PCM (Process Management)</strong> runs the improvement engine: the organisation's process objectives are set, current performance is understood, improvements are identified, prioritised, piloted and deployed. The post-project review is PCM's daily bread — lessons learned that actually flow back into PAL updates rather than into a folder named "lessons". <strong>GOV (Governance)</strong> is senior management's own practice area: leadership sets process expectations, provides resources, reviews status, and visibly holds the organisation accountable. Appraisers interview executives for GOV — slideware cannot answer for them; a leadership team that can discuss process performance fluently is GOV fully implemented. <strong>II (Implementation Infrastructure)</strong> is the meta-PA that asks one sharp question: are the practices <em>habits</em> or <em>theatre</em>? It looks for the resourcing, the assigned responsibilities and the persistence that prove practices survive between appraisals. II is the model auditing its own sustainability — and the reason the "audit-season spike" pattern (familiar from the SOC 2 booklet) fails here too.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">What the Document Library — Enabling &amp; Improving PAs</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>PA</th><th>Signature artifacts</th><th>Typical weakness appraisers find</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>DAR</td><td>Decision records: criteria, alternatives, evaluation, rationale</td><td>Decisions documented after the fact, criteria reverse-engineered to fit</td></tr>
 <tr><td>OT</td><td>Training plan, needs analysis, attendance &amp; completion records, effectiveness checks</td><td>Mid-cycle hires missing from records; curriculum stale against process changes</td></tr>
 <tr><td>PAD</td><td>The PAL itself: standard processes, templates, tailoring guidance, version history</td><td>Assets exist but tailoring guidance absent — projects adapt invisibly</td></tr>
 <tr><td>CAR</td><td>Analysis sessions, root causes, systemic actions, before/after trend data</td><td>"Root cause: human error" — analysis stopping one 'why' too early</td></tr>
 <tr><td>PCM</td><td>Process objectives, improvement backlog, pilot results, deployment records</td><td>Lessons collected ceremonially, never converted into PAL changes</td></tr>
 <tr><td>GOV</td><td>Management review minutes on process performance, resourcing decisions</td><td>Leadership unable to discuss process status without the documentation team in the room</td></tr>
 <tr><td>II</td><td>Role assignments, budgets, evidence practices persisted between appraisals</td><td>Practice activity clustered suspiciously around appraisal dates</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: treating these seven as "the paperwork PAs" to backfill at the end.</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">The dependency runs the other way: PAD builds what every project tailors from; OT proves people know the processes they're interviewed about; CAR and PCM are the learning loop that makes standards worth having; GOV and II prove the whole system has an owner and a pulse. Backfill these and the appraiser sees an organisation wearing Level 3 as a costume.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Take Away — Chapter 6</div>
 <ol>
 <li>DAR, OT, PAD, CAR support the teams; PCM, GOV, II run and govern the improvement engine.</li>
 <li>OT's most common failure is unrecorded training — especially for mid-cycle joiners.</li>
 <li>CAR's closed loop (data → cause → systemic fix → verified trend) is peak Level 3 behaviour.</li>
 <li>GOV is answered by executives in person; II is answered by the calendar of your evidence.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

