<section class="chapter" id="cmmi-c7">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Seven</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">How the Appraisal Works —<br>SCAMPI Without the Mystery</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Certification arrives through a formal appraisal: a structured, multi-week investigation led by a licensed Lead Appraiser. Knowing the machinery — the appraisal types, the five phases, the characterisation scale, and who does what — turns appraisal week from an ordeal into a performance you've rehearsed.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">SCAMPI A / B / C</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Key roles</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Five phases</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">FI / LI / PI / NI</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Sampling</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Three Appraisals, One Ladder of Seriousness</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th></th><th>SCAMPI C</th><th>SCAMPI B</th><th>SCAMPI A</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>Purpose</td><td>Quick self-assessment — where do we stand?</td><td>Readiness check before the real thing</td><td>Formal certification appraisal</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Duration</td><td>Days</td><td>1–2 weeks</td><td>1–3 weeks on-site</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Output</td><td>Rough gap picture; not certifiable</td><td>Findings report; not certifiable</td><td>Official maturity rating, registered and published</td></tr>
 <tr><td>When</td><td>Early preparation</td><td>2–3 months before the A</td><td>When genuinely ready</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>
 <p class="fade-up">The C and B are rehearsals with falling stakes-tolerance: the C tells you which walls are missing; the B tells you whether the house passes inspection. Skipping them to save money is how organisations meet their gaps for the first time in front of the Lead Appraiser — the most expensive possible venue.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Who's Who — and Who Is Not Your Coach</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Four roles matter. The <strong>Lead Appraiser</strong> — licensed, independent — runs the SCAMPI A, makes final characterisation calls, signs the rating. They investigate; they do not advise. The <strong>consultant</strong> (our organization's equivalent of Xavier in the SOC 2 story) is the opposite: hired to find gaps, shape documentation, and run the B/C rehearsals — your greatest asset before the appraisal, and deliberately offstage during it. <strong>Appraisal Team Members</strong> extend the Lead Appraiser's reach through artifact review and interviews. And the <strong>Documentation Team — you</strong> — produce and organise the objective evidence, and answer interview questions about the practices you actually perform. The cleaner your understanding, the stronger both halves.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Five Phases of a SCAMPI A</h2>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>1 — Planning:</strong> scope agreed — which PAs, which projects sampled; appraisal plan signed; our organization names an Appraisal Coordinator for logistics. <strong>2 — Preparation:</strong> the heavy lift — objective evidence compiled and organised into Practice Area folders, mapped practice-by-practice. <strong>3 — Readiness review:</strong> the team pre-reads the evidence and flags gaps; this is the last cheap moment to strengthen weak spots. <strong>4 — On-site:</strong> artifact examination by day, structured interviews throughout, daily team consolidations each evening. Interviews dominate — this is where documents are tested against reality. <strong>5 — Findings and rating:</strong> every practice characterised, weaknesses aggregated, the maturity level determined, and the result registered with the certifying body and published.</p>

 <div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The characterisation scale</div>
 Each practice in each sampled project lands on a four-point scale: <strong>FI</strong> — Fully Implemented (artifacts + affirmations, no weaknesses); <strong>LI</strong> — Largely Implemented (minor weaknesses); <strong>PI</strong> — Partially Implemented (significant weaknesses or thin evidence); <strong>NI</strong> — Not Implemented. The formula behind FI is worth memorising: <em>artifact + interview + consistency across projects</em>. Any leg missing drops the rating.</div>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — an interview, replayed</div>
 Appraiser: "Walk me through how your project manages risk." Weak answer: "We follow the risk process in the PAL." (Recites policy — proves reading, not practice.) Strong answer: "Every other Monday we review the register — here's March's, when we raised the data-quality risk to red and pulled in a data engineer; the mitigation closed it by sprint nine." The strong answer names a real artifact, a real date, a real decision. Appraisers triangulate everything you say against the documents they've already read — which is why coached answers collapse and lived practice doesn't.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Sampling — Why Every Project Matters</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">The appraisal does not examine every our organization project; it samples a representative subset across work types. The catch: <em>you don't control the conversation inside the sample</em>, and all sampled projects must show the standard practices. This is the structural reason the documentation team preaches consistency — one immaculate flagship project cannot rescue a sampled sibling that kept its risks in someone's head. The weakest sampled project is the organisation, as far as the rating is concerned.</p>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Take Away — Chapter 7</div>
 <ol>
 <li>C and B appraisals are rehearsals; the A is the performance. Skip rehearsals at your peril.</li>
 <li>The consultant prepares you; the Lead Appraiser evaluates you. Never confuse the roles.</li>
 <li>FI = artifact + affirmation + cross-project consistency. Memorise the formula.</li>
 <li>Interviews verify documents against reality — lived practice is the only reliable script.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ CMMI CH 8 ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="cmmi-c8">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Eight</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Evidence &amp; the PAL —<br>The the documentation team's Home Ground</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Everything in this booklet converges here: what counts as objective evidence, how to write process descriptions that survive interviews, the three traps that sink documentation efforts, the art of tailoring, and the Process Asset Library — the physical embodiment of Level 3.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">Objective evidence</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Three artifact types</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Process descriptions</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Tailoring</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">The PAL</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Objective Evidence — Proof a Stranger Could Verify</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">"Objective evidence" is CMMI's term for proof: documentation, records or observations demonstrating a practice was actually performed. The word <em>objective</em> sets the bar — any reasonable person examining it should reach the same conclusion. The the documentation team's everyday test: <em>if a stranger saw this document with zero context, could they confirm the practice happened?</em> If they'd have to take your word for it, the evidence is weak. (SOC 2 readers will recognise the receipt principle from that booklet's Part II; the two audit worlds agree completely here.)</p>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>What it is</th><th>Examples</th><th>Common weakness</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td><strong>Direct artifacts</strong></td><td>Work products produced <em>by performing</em> the practice — the primary evidence</td><td>Project plans, risk registers, test reports, review records, design docs</td><td>Templates with unfilled fields — created, never used</td></tr>
 <tr><td><strong>Indirect artifacts</strong></td><td>Records that point to the practice happening</td><td>Meeting minutes discussing risks, email trails on requirement changes, training attendance</td><td>Overlooked — teams don't recognise emails and minutes as evidence</td></tr>
 <tr><td><strong>Affirmations</strong></td><td>Verbal/written statements from practitioners, gathered in interviews</td><td>Interview answers, management confirmations</td><td>Cannot stand alone — must corroborate artifacts</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Writing Process Descriptions That Survive Interviews</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">A process description is not a policy; it's an explanation of how work gets done, specific enough for an unfamiliar competent person to follow. The anatomy: <strong>purpose</strong> (why this process exists), <strong>scope</strong> (when and to whom it applies), <strong>roles</strong> (who does what), <strong>steps</strong> (the actual procedure, in order), <strong>outputs</strong> (work products produced), and <strong>tailoring guidance</strong> (permitted adaptations and their conditions). The voice matters: write what our organization <em>does</em>, in the present tense, not what it aspires to — because every sentence is a claim an interviewer can test.</p>

 <div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The three traps</div>
 <strong>1 — The aspirational document:</strong> describing the ideal future instead of today's reality; interviews expose the gap in minutes. Document reality first, then improve it. <strong>2 — The template cemetery:</strong> beautiful templates nobody fills in; every template needs companion evidence of use — filled instances, version histories, sign-offs. <strong>3 — The silo problem:</strong> documentation covering only the flagship project; sampling (Chapter 7) makes the weakest project the rating. Consistency across projects is the entire point of Level 3.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Tailoring — The L3 Superpower, Used Correctly</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Tailoring lets a project adapt the standard process to its context — the mechanism that keeps standards from becoming straitjackets. But tailoring is a <em>documented decision</em>, not an exemption slip. "We skipped peer reviews because they felt unnecessary" is non-compliance wearing a smile. "We used lightweight peer reviews for this deliverable class, as permitted by the PR tailoring guidance, recorded in the project plan §4" — that is tailoring: the deviation is named, justified, authorised by the guidance, and recorded where an appraiser will look.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The PAL — Level 3 Made Physical</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">The Process Asset Library is the central repository of our organization's standard processes, templates, tailoring guidance, examples and lessons learned. It is the first thing an appraisal scrutinises, against four questions: Is it <strong>accessible</strong> to all staff? Is it <strong>current</strong> — owned, versioned, reviewed? Is it <strong>used</strong> — can projects show what they tailored from it? Does it <strong>learn</strong> — are recent projects' lessons visibly incorporated? A PAL that fails the last two is a library in the archaeological sense.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the PAL walkthrough</div>
 An appraiser opens our organization's PAL and picks the estimation process: version 3.2, owner named, last reviewed this year — good. They ask a project lead to show their estimate: it uses template v3.2, the tailoring log notes the team dropped the function-point sheet (permitted for maintenance work) — better. Then the appraiser checks the lessons-learned register: a post-project review eight months ago recommended adding a data-migration line item to the template, and v3.2's changelog shows exactly that change — <em>that</em> is the loop closing, and it is what Level 3 looks like from inside.</div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Take Away — Chapter 8</div>
 <ol>
 <li>Evidence must pass the stranger test; affirmations corroborate artifacts, never replace them.</li>
 <li>Process descriptions are present-tense claims about reality — every sentence is interview-testable.</li>
 <li>Tailoring = named deviation + rationale + permitted by guidance + recorded. Anything less is non-compliance.</li>
 <li>The PAL is judged on access, currency, usage and learning — not on elegance.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ CMMI CH 9 ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="cmmi-c9">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Nine</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">CMMI at our organization —<br>Why This Is Personal</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Frameworks feel abstract until you map them onto the work in this building. This chapter connects CMMI to our organization's actual portfolio, its other certifications, its agile delivery reality, and the division of labour that keeps Level 3 alive between appraisals.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">The stakes</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Agile ↔ CMMI mapping</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">One evidence engine</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Who does what</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Stakes Are Not Abstract</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">our organization builds national-scale government systems, donor-funded education platforms, and identity-management infrastructure. At that scale the practices CMMI encodes stop being audit hygiene and become public-interest engineering: poorly managed requirements produce systems that fail at national rollout; skipped peer reviews ship defects into government production; weak risk management converts client crises into our organization crises. CMMI L3 is simultaneously a <strong>tender qualification</strong> (procurement shortlists demand it), a <strong>delivery insurance policy</strong> (the practices demonstrably reduce failure), and a <strong>client-trust signal</strong> sitting alongside ISO 9001, ISO 27001 and the SOC 2 attestation in our organization's credibility stack.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Agile Delivery, CMMI Evidence</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">our organization's teams deliver iteratively, and CMMI v3.0 was explicitly built to accommodate that. The practical move is recognition — seeing the ceremonies you already run as the practices the model names, then keeping their residue:</p>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>What the team already does</th><th>What CMMI calls it</th><th>What to keep as evidence</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>Backlog refinement, acceptance criteria</td><td>RDM</td><td>Groomed backlog exports, criteria in tickets, change discussions</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Sprint planning &amp; velocity-based forecasting</td><td>EST + PLAN</td><td>Sprint plans, velocity data, re-forecasts</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Stand-ups, burndowns, sprint reviews</td><td>MC</td><td>Burndown snapshots, review notes, action items</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Pull-request reviews</td><td>PR</td><td>Review threads, findings, merge approvals</td></tr>
 <tr><td>CI/CD pipelines, branch protection</td><td>CM</td><td>Pipeline configs, release tags, change approvals</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Retrospectives</td><td>IRP / CAR / PCM</td><td>Retro notes, improvement actions, closed-loop follow-ups</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Definition of done, UAT</td><td>VV</td><td>DoD checklists, test reports, UAT sign-offs</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>
 <p class="fade-up">The discipline this table demands is small but real: artifacts must be <em>kept</em> (retro notes that evaporate prove nothing), <em>linked</em> to the standard process they instantiate, and <em>consistent</em> across squads — the same three requirements sampling will test.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">One Evidence Engine, Three Frameworks</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">The deepest efficiency available to the documentation team is designing artifacts once for all of our organization's obligations. The risk register serves CMMI's RSK, ISO 9001's clause 6 and SOC 2's CC3. The incident log serves IRP, ISO 27001's incident clauses and SOC 2's CC7. Training records serve OT and SOC 2's HR controls; supplier files serve SAM and vendor-risk controls; CAPA tracking serves CAR, ISO nonconformity handling and SOC 2's audit domain. A single well-structured evidence repository with framework tags beats three parallel bureaucracies in cost, in consistency — and in the eyes of every auditor who sees that the system is one system.</p>

 <div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Who keeps L3 alive — the cast, CMMI edition</div>
 The same division of labour that runs our organization's SOC 2 calendar runs CMMI: the <strong>the documentation team</strong> curates the PAL, the trackers and the evidence repository; <strong>project teams</strong> generate the daily artifacts (plans, registers, reviews, retros); <strong>HR</strong> owns training records and onboarding orientation (OT); <strong>IT</strong> keeps the toolchain evidence (CM, pipelines, logs); <strong>Management</strong> answers for GOV in person and funds the rest; and the <strong>consultant</strong> runs gap analyses and rehearsal appraisals. No practice area belongs to one chair.</div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Take Away — Chapter 9</div>
 <ol>
 <li>For our organization's portfolio, CMMI practices are public-interest engineering, not ceremony.</li>
 <li>Agile ceremonies already perform most practices — keep, link and standardise their residue.</li>
 <li>Build one evidence engine for CMMI + ISO + SOC 2; tag artifacts, don't triplicate them.</li>
 <li>Level 3 is a team sport with the same cast as every other compliance effort in this building.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

