<section class="chapter" id="cmmi-c10">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Ten</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Sustaining Level 3 —<br>Myths, FAQs &amp; the Long Game</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Passing the appraisal is the starting gun, not the finish line. Ratings expire — which is exactly why our organization recertifies — and practices erode quietly unless deliberately maintained. This closing chapter covers the habits that keep L3 alive, busts the persistent myths, and answers the questions your colleagues actually ask.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">Why certifications erode</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Sustaining habits</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Myth-busting</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">FAQs</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Re-appraisal readiness</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Why Certifications Erode</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">The pattern is everywhere: heavy investment, successful appraisal, then a slow fade — until the next re-appraisal effectively starts from zero. The root cause is always the same: the certification was treated as a <em>goal</em> rather than a <em>standard</em>. The mindset that survives is the inverted one: <em>we are certified because we do the practices — and we do the practices because they make the work better.</em> Concretely, four habits carry the weight:</p>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Habit</th><th>What it means in practice</th><th>Cadence</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>PAL maintenance</td><td>Review process docs, archive stale versions, fold in lessons learned; a named custodian owns it</td><td>Quarterly + after each project</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Genuine post-project reviews</td><td>Honest retros feeding IRP/CAR/PCM — not box-ticking ceremonies</td><td>Every project close</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Fresh training records</td><td>CMMI orientation for every new hire; curriculum updated when processes change — OT's classic re-appraisal trap</td><td>Per hire; curriculum semi-annually</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Internal PQA audits</td><td>Scheduled spot-checks that projects use the standard processes; normalised, not audit-season panic</td><td>Monthly / per milestone</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>
 <p class="fade-up">And the calendar item that matters most: <strong>12–18 months before expiry</strong>, run a SCAMPI C self-assessment, fix what it finds, then bring the consultant in for a B. Rehearsals are cheap exactly in proportion to how early they happen.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Myth-Busting</h2>
 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">"CMMI is just paperwork — it doesn't improve anything."</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">Documentation is the <em>evidence</em>, not the goal. Organisations pursuing CMMI honestly report measurable gains in on-time delivery, defect rates and cost predictability — the documents are the exhaust of the engine, not the engine.</div>
 </div>
 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">"We're too small for CMMI."</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">v2.0 was designed to scale; organisations of 10–15 people have achieved L3. Practices tailor to size — consistency matters, bureaucratic volume doesn't.</div>
 </div>
 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">"Agile and CMMI are opposites."</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">The model explicitly supports agile delivery. Sprints, retros, backlogs and code reviews <em>are</em> the practices (see Chapter Nine's mapping) — they just need their evidence kept and standardised.</div>
 </div>
 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">"Once we pass, we're done."</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">Ratings expire, and surface-level compliance erodes fastest. The habit is the asset; the certificate merely verifies it — which is why our organization treats recertification as routine, not crisis.</div>
 </div>
 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">"The consultant will write our documentation."</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">A consultant guides, reviews, and rehearses you. Processes ghost-written by an outsider collapse in interviews, because the people performing them don't recognise the words. Own your documentation.</div>
 </div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>Will appraisers interview me personally?</strong> Quite possibly. The SCAMPI A interviews the people who perform the practices — including the documentation team. You'll be asked how you do specific work, what it produces, and where it lives. Understanding, not memorisation, is the preparation.</p>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>Does every our organization project need to be covered?</strong> No — the appraisal samples a representative subset. But every <em>sampled</em> project must demonstrate the practices, and you don't choose the sample's weakest moment. Hence: consistency across all projects, always.</p>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>How is this different from our ISO 9001 audit?</strong> ISO audits assess the quality system broadly; CMMI appraisals drill into specific engineering and management practices, probe project artifacts in depth, and triangulate across interviews and multiple projects. Expect it to be longer and more intensive.</p>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>What if we don't pass?</strong> An appraisal can return a lower level or flag practice areas as insufficient — rare with proper rehearsal (the B exists precisely to catch this), and the commoner outcome is passing with noted improvement opportunities. Preparation converts risk into findings you already knew about.</p>

 <div class="pull-quote fade-up"><p>"The practices CMMI encodes are hard-won lessons from decades of engineering experience. Followed genuinely, they make it far more likely that the work you do will succeed — and endure."</p></div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Take Away — Chapter 10, and the booklet</div>
 <ol>
 <li>Certifications erode when compliance replaces conviction; the habit is the asset.</li>
 <li>Four habits sustain L3: a living PAL, honest retros, fresh training records, routine internal audits.</li>
 <li>Start re-appraisal readiness 12–18 months out with a SCAMPI C; rehearse before performing.</li>
 <li>You — the documentation team — are our organization's institutional memory for CMMI. Own that role.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

