<section class="chapter" id="soc2-ch8">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Eight</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">our organization's SOC 2<br>Journey</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">This chapter documents how our organization actually went through the SOC 2 process — the real timeline, the vendors engaged, the obstacles encountered, and how certification was ultimately achieved. Reading the theory is one thing; knowing what it looked like in practice at our organization is another.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">Why our organization pursued SOC 2</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Vendors &amp; partners</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">The first audit (2024)</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Remediation phase</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Type II achieved (April 2026)</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
 <h2 class="section fade-up">Why our organization Pursued SOC 2</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">our organization's SOC 2 initiative was not an internally-driven quality programme — it was driven by a direct client requirement. <strong>InfoIMAGE</strong>, a key our organization client, mandated SOC 2 Type II compliance as a condition of the ongoing commercial relationship. This is a common pattern in the industry: enterprise and financial-sector clients increasingly require SOC 2 as a baseline vendor qualification, and the request arrives with a real deadline attached.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">Beyond satisfying InfoIMAGE's requirements, leadership recognised that SOC 2 certification would strengthen our organization's competitive position in international procurement — particularly for donor-funded programmes and regional enterprise clients applying due-diligence processes to their technology vendors.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up">
 <div class="callout-label">The Driving Client</div>
 <p><strong>InfoIMAGE</strong> initially required a full SOC 2 Type II report covering the 2024 calendar year, with a delivery deadline by the end of May 2025. This compressed timeline shaped every decision made in the early phase of the programme.</p>
 </div>

 <h3 class="sub fade-up">The Vendors our organization Engaged</h3>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up">
 <table>
 <thead><tr><th>Partner</th><th>Role</th><th>What They Did for our organization</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>Orcwiz (Xavier)</td><td>Compliance Consultant</td><td>Guided our organization through readiness — identified control gaps, advised on policy development, prepared the team for audit walkthroughs. The consultant relationship, not the auditor relationship.</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Attinkom LLC</td><td>CPA Audit Firm</td><td>Conducted the independent attestation audits. Issued the official SOC 2 reports. As the independent auditor, Attinkom's role was to evaluate and report — not advise on remediation.</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table>
 </div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Phase 1 — The First Audit (Early 2025)</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">With InfoIMAGE's deadline creating urgency, our organization moved quickly to engage its audit partners. Attinkom LLC and our organization finalised an audit timeline that was aggressive by industry standards: a kickoff meeting on <strong>May 5, 2025</strong>, with a draft audit report targeted by <strong>May 31, 2025</strong>. The actual report was received on <strong>June 29, 2025</strong> — slightly beyond the original target but within acceptable range.</p>

 <div class="callout fade-up">
 <div class="callout-label">What the First Report Established</div>
 <p>The initial SOC 2 report covered the 2024 calendar year. Like many first-time SOC 2 reports, it identified gaps — controls that were not yet operating with the consistency or documentation quality required for an unqualified Type II opinion. This is entirely normal and expected. The value of the first report was precisely in surfacing what needed to improve.</p>
 </div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Phase 2 — Remediation (Late 2025 – Early 2026)</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Following the initial report, our organization entered a structured remediation phase. <strong>Ridhwan Chowdhury</strong> was assigned to project manage the SOC 2 initiative and lead evidence collection across the organisation. This is a significant responsibility — the project manager for a SOC 2 programme sits at the intersection of IT, security, HR, legal, and every line of business that owns in-scope controls.</p>

 <h3 class="sub fade-up">Key Remediation Tasks (as of September 2025)</h3>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up">
 <table>
 <thead><tr><th>Remediation Item</th><th>Owner</th><th>Status (Sept 2025)</th><th>TSC Relevance</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>Antivirus &amp; VAPT (Vulnerability Assessment &amp; Penetration Testing) implementation</td><td>IT Security</td><td>In progress</td><td>CC7 — System Operations</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Patch management process formalisation</td><td>IT Operations</td><td>In progress</td><td>CC7 — System Operations</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Cybersecurity Insurance purchase</td><td>Tanveer Hasan</td><td>Assigned</td><td>CC9 — Risk Mitigation</td></tr>
 <tr><td>G Suite MFA enforcement for all accounts</td><td>IT Operations</td><td>In progress</td><td>CC6 — Logical Access Controls</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Security policy library — drafting and approving 54 policies</td><td>Compliance / Documentation Team</td><td>In progress</td><td>CC1, CC5 — Control Environment &amp; Activities</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table>
 </div>

 <div class="callout teal fade-up">
 <div class="callout-label">The 54-Policy Library</div>
 <p>Drafting, reviewing, and obtaining management approval for 54 security policies is a substantial undertaking. Each policy must reflect actual our organization practice — not a generic template — and must be approved, communicated, and version-controlled. This work forms the documentary foundation of the entire SOC 2 programme.</p>
 </div>

 <h3 class="sub fade-up">The Type I Decision — Skipped</h3>
 <p class="fade-up">In late 2025, InfoIMAGE requested a short-term SOC 2 <strong>Type I</strong> attestation focused only on the controls that had failed in the initial audit, with a target completion date of November 14, 2025. This would have provided InfoIMAGE with interim assurance while the full Type II remediation continued.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">However, after discussion between our organization and <strong>Jonathan Weismann</strong> at InfoIMAGE, the decision was made to skip the Type I assessment entirely and proceed directly to the second full SOC 2 Type II audit. This was a commercially sensible decision — it avoided the cost and effort of an intermediate Type I while keeping focus on the full Type II programme.</p>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Skipping Type I means our organization had no assurance to offer InfoIMAGE in the interim.</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">InfoIMAGE had the initial Type II report from June 2025, which already described the control environment as of the 2024 period. The decision to skip Type I was made with InfoIMAGE's agreement — an informed commercial decision, not a gap in coverage.</div>
 </div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Phase 3 — The Second Audit and Certification (2026)</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">The second SOC 2 Type II audit was planned to cover the <strong>full 2025 calendar year (January 1 to December 31, 2025)</strong>, with fieldwork commencing in the first week of January 2026. This 12-month observation window gave the auditors a full year of evidence against which to evaluate operating effectiveness — the strongest possible basis for a clean report.</p>

 <div class="callout green fade-up">
 <div class="callout-label">SOC 2 Type II Achieved — April 2026</div>
 <p>The final SOC 2 Type II report, covering the period of sustained compliance, was received by our organization in <strong>April 2026</strong>. our organization successfully achieved SOC 2 Type II compliance — the gold standard attestation that enterprise and government clients require. The journey from first engagement to clean certification took approximately 15 months of sustained work.</p>
 </div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">What's Next — Maintaining Compliance</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">With the Type II report in hand, our organization's current focus is on creating a <strong>yearly SOC 2 maintenance calendar</strong> — a structured, owner-assigned schedule of all periodic control activities that ensures the next audit period's evidence is being generated continuously. This is exactly the operational discipline described in Chapter 7: turning compliance from an annual project into a sustainable year-round practice.</p>

 <div class="callout navy fade-up">
 <div class="callout-label">our organization SOC 2 Timeline at a Glance</div>
