 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · The Control Playbook</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Inside our organization's<br>ISMS Calendar</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Part I explained what SOC 2 is. Part II goes a level deeper: it walks through the eleven security domains in our organization's 2026 ISMS Calendar — the control-by-control playbook drafted with Xavier for sustaining compliance. Each chapter takes one domain and answers four questions: <strong>what</strong> the controls are, <strong>why</strong> auditors care, <strong>what activities</strong> our organization must perform through the year, and <strong>what evidence</strong> proves it happened — including who produces that evidence and how.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">11 domains</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">~70 controls</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">830+ evidence items</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Real real-world scenarios</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
 <h2 class="section fade-up">How to Read Part II</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">A SOC 2 control is a <em>promise</em>. The evidence is the <em>receipt</em>. Everything in the ISMS Calendar exists because during the 2024 audit, our organization made promises in its System Description — and the auditor asked for receipts. Where receipts were missing, the report recorded an <strong>exception</strong>. The calendar is designed so that next year, no receipt is ever missing: every control has a domain, an owner, a cadence, and a defined list of evidence.</p>
 <div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The cast of characters</div>
 Throughout Part II you will meet the same six names from the NC List: <strong>Xavier</strong> (external consultant — frameworks, assessments, audit artifacts), the <strong>the documentation team</strong> (policies, trackers, minutes — the compliance engine room), <strong>HR</strong> (everything touching people), <strong>IT</strong> (logs, configurations, scans — the largest evidence producer), <strong>Management</strong> (approvals, reviews, sign-offs, spending), and <strong>Admin</strong> (the physical world: premises, vendors, utilities). No control in the calendar is a one-person job.</div>
 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The golden rule of evidence</div>
 <ol>
 <li>If it isn't written down, it didn't happen.</li>
 <li>If it's written down but not dated, it didn't happen <em>during the audit period</em>.</li>
 <li>If it's dated but nobody approved it, it happened — but nobody was accountable.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ PART II · CH 1 — GOVERNANCE ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="soc2-d1">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · Chapter One</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Governance —<br>The Tone at the Top</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Every other domain in this booklet hangs off this one. Governance is where our organization proves that security is not an IT hobby but a management system: policies exist, leadership reviews them, an internal audit checks them, and employees actually know about them. In the ISMS Calendar this is controls ISMS-001, ISMS-007, ISMS-002, ISMS-005 and ISMS-008.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">ISMS-001 · Policy suite</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">ISMS-007 · Policy lifecycle</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">ISMS-002 · Management review</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">ISMS-005 · Internal audit</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">ISMS-008 · Handbook &amp; ethics</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Why Auditors Start Here</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">SOC 2's Common Criteria CC1 ("Control Environment") borrows a phrase from the COSO framework: <strong>tone at the top</strong>. The logic is simple — if leadership doesn't visibly own security, no firewall configuration will save the company, because controls decay the moment nobody senior is watching. So before an auditor ever looks at a server, they ask: <em>show me your approved policies, show me the meeting where management reviewed them, and show me that your staff acknowledged them.</em></p>
 <p class="fade-up">This is also why governance failures are so expensive in an audit. A missing patch is one exception. A missing management-review process suggests <em>every other control might be unsupervised</em> — and auditors start probing harder everywhere else.</p>

 <div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Real real-world scenario — how this bit us in 2024</div>
 The 2024 report logged an exception on <strong>Disciplinary Policy Enforcement</strong> (NC #5): our organization said violations would be disciplined, but had no documented policy and no log of incidents. The fix took six people: the documentation team drafted the policy and walked HR through it, HR took it to management, communicated it to every employee, started a violations log, and set an annual review reminder. That's governance in miniature — a document, a communication trail, a log, and a recurring calendar event.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Controls, Decoded</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Control</th><th>What it really asks</th><th>Cadence</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>ISMS-001</td><td>Does a complete, approved set of ISMS policies exist (security, acceptable use, access, incident, backup…)?</td><td>Annual review</td></tr>
 <tr><td>ISMS-007</td><td>Is there a living lifecycle — review tracker, version history, review comments — proving policies don't just sit in a folder?</td><td>Annual + on change</td></tr>
 <tr><td>ISMS-002</td><td>Does management formally review the ISMS — risks, audits, KPIs, corrective actions — and leave minutes behind?</td><td>Quarterly/biannual</td></tr>
 <tr><td>ISMS-005</td><td>Does our organization audit <em>itself</em> before the external auditor arrives, and fix what it finds?</td><td>Annual</td></tr>
 <tr><td>ISMS-008</td><td>Handbook, code of conduct, ethics &amp; disciplinary policies — published, acknowledged, enforced.</td><td>Annual</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Year in Activities</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">To stay compliant, the calendar turns governance into a routine. <strong>Once a year</strong>: every policy gets re-read, redlined, version-bumped and re-approved; the internal audit runs end-to-end (plan → checklist → fieldwork → findings → corrective actions → closure); the handbook is re-acknowledged by all staff. <strong>Each quarter or half-year</strong>: a management review meeting walks a fixed agenda — risk register movement, audit status, KPI dashboard, open corrective actions — and ends with documented decisions. <strong>Continuously</strong>: new joiners acknowledge policies during onboarding, and any policy change triggers re-communication.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the management review meeting that counts</div>
 Imagine the auditor asks: "Prove leadership oversees security." A calendar invite is not enough. What works is a pack: an <em>agenda</em> sent before the meeting, <em>minutes</em> naming attendees and decisions ("approved budget for VAPT retest", "accepted residual risk R-14"), an <em>attendance record</em>, the <em>KPI dashboard</em> screenshotted that day, and an <em>action item tracker</em> where last quarter's items are visibly closed. One meeting, six artifacts. That is why ISMS-002 lists ten evidence items.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Evidence Shelf — and How Each Item Is Made</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Evidence</th><th>How it's produced</th><th>Owner</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>Approved ISMS policies</td><td>the documentation team drafts/revises in the controlled template; Management signs; PDF stored in the evidence repository</td><td>the documentation team → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Policy review tracker</td><td>A simple register: policy name, version, last review, next due, reviewer — updated at every review</td><td>the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Version history &amp; review comments</td><td>Kept inside each document's revision table; redline comments saved, not deleted</td><td>the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Communication records</td><td>The all-staff email/Slack post announcing each policy, archived with date</td><td>the documentation team / HR</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Employee acknowledgements</td><td>HR collects signed forms or e-acknowledgements; tracker shows 100% coverage incl. new joiners</td><td>HR</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Mgmt review agenda / minutes / attendance</td><td>Standing template; the documentation team writes minutes within 48h; chair approves them</td><td>the documentation team → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Internal audit plan, checklist, report</td><td>Xavier defines scope and template, conducts fieldwork; the documentation team logs findings and tracks remediation to closure</td><td>Xavier + the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>CAPA / corrective action tracker</td><td>Every finding gets an owner, a target date and closure evidence — the auditor will sample it</td><td>the documentation team</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: "We'll write the minutes later, before the audit."</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">Backdated minutes are the fastest way to lose an auditor's trust. Metadata (file creation dates, email timestamps) betrays reconstruction. The calendar exists precisely so artifacts are created <em>at the moment of the activity</em> — which is also when they're cheapest to make: ten minutes after a meeting, not ten hours in audit week.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Chapter takeaways</div>
 <ol>
 <li>Governance is the control environment — auditors read weakness here as weakness everywhere.</li>
 <li>Every governance activity produces a paper pair: the <em>thing</em> (policy, meeting, audit) and the <em>proof</em> (tracker, minutes, acknowledgement).</li>
 <li>The internal audit (ISMS-005) is our organization's rehearsal: find exceptions yourself, cheaply, before the external auditor finds them expensively.</li>
 <li>Six roles share the load — no governance control is completed by a single person.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ PART II · CH 2 — RISK & COMPLIANCE ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="soc2-d2">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · Chapter Two</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Risk &amp; Compliance —<br>Knowing What Can Hurt You</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Eleven controls (RISK-001 to RISK-011) make this the broadest domain in the calendar. The theme: our organization must <em>systematically</em> identify what can go wrong — technical risks, fraud, privacy harm, legal exposure, vendor failures, customer commitments — and show a written trail of evaluating and treating each one. This domain produced four exceptions in the 2024 report, more than any other.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">Risk assessment &amp; register</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Fraud risk</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">DPIA &amp; privacy risk</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Laws &amp; regulations</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Vendor risk</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Cyber insurance</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Customer SLAs</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Data retention</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Why This Domain Exists</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">SOC 2's CC3 criteria demand that an organisation doesn't just <em>react</em> to incidents but <em>anticipates</em> them. The auditor's mental model: a company that has never written down its risks doesn't know which controls matter, so all its other controls are accidents. The risk assessment is the spine — every other control should trace back to a risk it mitigates.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">In practice this domain runs on four registers: the <strong>risk register</strong> (what can hurt us), the <strong>compliance register</strong> (which laws bind us), the <strong>vendor inventory</strong> (who we depend on), and the <strong>data inventory</strong> (what we hold and how long we may keep it). Each register feeds an annual cycle of assessment → treatment → management acceptance.</p>

 <div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Real real-world scenario — the 2024 exceptions</div>
 Four findings landed here. <strong>NC #35/36</strong>: no annual IT security risk assessment and no formal risk evaluation/mitigation process — Xavier had to build the framework and template, run a comprehensive assessment, and develop the treatment plan, while IT documented the formal procedure and HR convened a risk review meeting. <strong>NC #43</strong>: no insurance against cyber incidents — Management had to research vendors and buy a policy. <strong>NC #47</strong>: no vendor risk assessment — Xavier wrote the policy and scoring criteria; Admin built the central vendor inventory, formalised contracts, and assessed every current vendor. Note the pattern: the consultant creates the <em>method</em>, internal teams create the <em>operating records</em>.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Controls, Decoded</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Control</th><th>What it really asks</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>RISK-001</td><td>An annual, methodology-driven risk assessment: register, scoring matrix, treatment plan, management sign-off, residual-risk acceptance.</td></tr>
 <tr><td>RISK-002</td><td>Fraud risk specifically — could someone inside or outside abuse assets, falsify reporting, or circumvent controls? (CC3.3 calls this out by name.)</td></tr>
 <tr><td>RISK-003</td><td>Privacy impact: DPIAs, data flow diagrams, records of processing — what personal data moves where, and what could harm the data subject?</td></tr>
 <tr><td>RISK-004 / 005</td><td>A register of applicable laws and a mechanism for noticing when they change (legal monitoring, regulatory update tracker, policy revisions).</td></tr>
 <tr><td>RISK-006 / 007</td><td>Third parties: due diligence before engagement, SOC/ISO reports collected, NDAs and SLAs signed, performance reviewed.</td></tr>
 <tr><td>RISK-008</td><td>Cyber insurance: coverage matched to assessed risk, renewed on time, claim procedure known before it's needed.</td></tr>
 <tr><td>RISK-009</td><td>Customer commitments: SLAs tracked, availability measured, escalations and breaches handled and reviewed.</td></tr>
 <tr><td>RISK-010 / 011</td><td>Privacy compliance and retention: policies, consent records, a retention schedule, and <em>proof of disposal</em> when time is up.</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">How a Risk Assessment Actually Works</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Demystified, it's five steps. <strong>1 — Inventory:</strong> list assets (systems, data, people, premises) — this is why the asset inventory appears as evidence here, not just in IT. <strong>2 — Identify:</strong> for each asset, ask what threats apply (ransomware, insider misuse, vendor outage, flood) and what vulnerabilities exist. <strong>3 — Score:</strong> likelihood × impact on the scoring matrix; this converts argument into arithmetic. <strong>4 — Treat:</strong> for every red cell choose mitigate / transfer (insurance!) / avoid / accept — with an owner and a date. <strong>5 — Accept:</strong> management formally signs the residual risk. The signature is the point: it proves leadership <em>saw</em> the risk and chose, rather than drifted.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the vendor you forgot</div>
 our organization uses a small local courier to move backup drives between offices. Nobody thinks of them as a "vendor" — until the auditor samples the vendor inventory and asks why a company that physically transports client data has no NDA, no risk rating and no contract on file. This is why Admin's "boring" central vendor inventory is a control: risk lives precisely in the suppliers nobody remembered. Rule of thumb: if a third party touches data, premises, or production, it belongs in the inventory with a risk score.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Evidence Shelf — and How Each Item Is Made</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Evidence</th><th>How it's produced</th><th>Owner</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>Risk methodology &amp; scoring matrix</td><td>Written once by Xavier, approved by Management, re-reviewed annually</td><td>Xavier</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Risk register &amp; treatment plan</td><td>Living spreadsheet/tool updated during the annual assessment and whenever a new risk surfaces (incident, new vendor, new law)</td><td>Xavier + IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Risk review meeting records</td><td>Minutes of the annual (minimum) review where management debates and accepts residual risk</td><td>the documentation team → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>DPIA reports &amp; data flow diagrams</td><td>For each system processing personal data: what's collected, where it flows, lawful basis, harms, mitigations</td><td>Xavier</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Compliance register</td><td>Table of applicable laws/regulations/contractual obligations, each mapped to an internal owner and control</td><td>Xavier + the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Vendor inventory, due diligence, NDAs</td><td>Admin maintains the inventory; collects SOC 2/ISO reports from critical vendors annually; files signed NDAs/SLAs</td><td>Admin</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Insurance policy &amp; renewal records</td><td>Management procures; the documentation team diarises renewal 60 days ahead; coverage compared against the risk assessment</td><td>Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>SLA performance &amp; availability records</td><td>IT exports uptime/ticket metrics; reviewed in customer and management meetings</td><td>IT → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Retention schedule &amp; disposal records</td><td>the documentation team owns the schedule; disposal events (wipes, shreds) are logged with date, method, approver</td><td>the documentation team + IT</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: a risk register written once and never touched.</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">An auditor checks the register's <em>dates</em>. If every entry was created the same afternoon thirteen months ago, the "process" is visibly a one-off. Healthy registers show movement: new risks after incidents, scores changing after mitigations, treatment actions closing. Five minutes of updates per month beats a heroic annual rewrite.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Chapter takeaways</div>
 <ol>
 <li>Risk assessment is the spine of SOC 2 — every control should answer to a risk on the register.</li>
 <li>Four registers run the domain: risks, laws, vendors, data. Keep them alive, not annual.</li>
 <li>Residual risk needs a management signature — choosing a risk is fine; drifting into one is a finding.</li>
 <li>Insurance is risk <em>transfer</em>: buy it to match the assessment, and know the claim procedure in advance.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ PART II · CH 3 — ACCESS MANAGEMENT ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="soc2-d3">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · Chapter Three</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Access Management —<br>Who Can Touch What</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Nine controls (IAM-001 to IAM-009) govern the single question auditors care most about: is access to systems, data and premises granted deliberately, reviewed regularly, and removed immediately? Access findings are the most common SOC 2 exceptions industry-wide, because access drifts silently — people change roles, leave, or accumulate rights nobody remembers granting.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">Access reviews</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Privileged access</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">MFA</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Passwords &amp; lockout</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Joiners &amp; leavers</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">VPN / remote</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Physical access</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Logic of Least Privilege</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Everything in IAM derives from one principle: a person should hold exactly the access their current role requires — no more, no less, no longer. The <strong>RBAC matrix</strong> (role-based access control) is the master document: a grid of roles × systems that says a backend developer gets repo + staging, a finance officer gets the ERP, and <em>nobody</em> gets production "just in case". Every grant, review and revocation is then measured against that grid. This is why the RBAC matrix shows up as evidence in four separate controls — it's the yardstick.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">The lifecycle has three moments. <strong>Joiner</strong> (IAM-006): access requested on a form, approved by a manager, provisioned by ticket — three artifacts before day one. <strong>Mover</strong>: role changes trigger re-evaluation (the quarterly access review catches what tickets miss). <strong>Leaver</strong> (IAM-007): the offboarding checklist runs the same day — accounts disabled, VPN cut, assets returned, HR signs off. The auditor's favourite test: pick five leavers from the HR list and demand proof each account died within policy timelines. One stale account = one exception.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the access review that earns its keep</div>
 Quarterly, IT exports user listings from every critical system — not screenshots of an admin panel taken whenever, but dated exports. A reviewer (the system owner, not the person who granted access) walks each name against the RBAC matrix: <em>still employed? still this role? still needs this?</em> Three rows get flagged: an intern who left in July, a developer who moved to QA but kept deploy rights, and a shared "temp-admin" account nobody owns. Each flag becomes a revocation ticket. The auditor receives: the export, the reviewer's sign-off, and the closed tickets. That trio — listing, review, action — is the universal anatomy of review evidence.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Controls, Decoded</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Control</th><th>What it really asks</th><th>Cadence</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>IAM-001</td><td>Periodic user access reviews against the RBAC matrix, with revocations actioned and terminated users validated gone.</td><td>Quarterly</td></tr>
 <tr><td>IAM-002</td><td>Privileged (admin) access: separately listed, separately justified, MFA-protected, activity-logged, reviewed harder.</td><td>Quarterly</td></tr>
 <tr><td>IAM-003</td><td>MFA enforced everywhere that matters — with enrollment records and config screenshots to prove "enforced", not "available".</td><td>Continuous</td></tr>
 <tr><td>IAM-004 / 005</td><td>Password complexity, expiry, and lockout/inactivity-timeout settings matching the written policy.</td><td>Continuous</td></tr>
 <tr><td>IAM-006</td><td>Joiner provisioning: request → approval → ticket, never verbal.</td><td>Per event</td></tr>
 <tr><td>IAM-007</td><td>Leaver deprovisioning: same-day revocation, asset return, HR sign-off.</td><td>Per event</td></tr>
 <tr><td>IAM-008</td><td>VPN/remote access: approved users only, MFA-validated, logged and monitored.</td><td>Quarterly review</td></tr>
 <tr><td>IAM-009</td><td>Physical access: biometric/card records, visitor logs, server-room lists, CCTV — the building is a system too.</td><td>Quarterly review</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Real our organization context</div>
 The 2024 cycle flagged physical-access gaps on the "Other" list — central door access control (IT), guest sign-in sheets, external camera coverage and power backup for access systems (Admin). IAM-009 is where those fixes become routine evidence: monthly-reviewed biometric logs, a visitor book that's actually filled in, and CCTV retention that matches policy. Physical access is the easiest control to demonstrate and the most embarrassing to fail — an auditor who walks in unbadged and unchallenged has already written the finding.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Evidence Shelf — and How Each Item Is Made</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Evidence</th><th>How it's produced</th><th>Owner</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>User / privileged-user listings</td><td>System-generated exports with visible date and source system; never retyped into a spreadsheet by hand</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>RBAC matrix</td><td>Maintained by IT, approved by Management whenever roles change</td><td>IT → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Reviewer sign-offs</td><td>Review file annotated keep/revoke per row, signed and dated by the system owner</td><td>Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>MFA configs &amp; enrollment</td><td>Screenshots of tenant policy (e.g. "MFA: required, no exceptions") plus enrollment report; exceptions documented and approved</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Onboarding / offboarding packs</td><td>HR opens the checklist; IT closes tickets; HR confirms; the completed checklist is the evidence</td><td>HR + IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>VPN logs &amp; approvals</td><td>Access list reviewed quarterly; logs retained per policy; anomalies escalated</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Visitor logs, biometric records, CCTV</td><td>Admin keeps the registers and retention; spot-checked monthly</td><td>Admin</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: "Everyone here is trusted — we're a small company."</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">SOC 2 doesn't doubt your people; it doubts your <em>memory</em>. In a small company one admin leaving with credentials intact is a bigger share of total risk, not a smaller one. Least privilege also protects employees — nobody wants to be the person whose unused production access is questioned after an incident.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Chapter takeaways</div>
 <ol>
 <li>The RBAC matrix is the yardstick; reviews, grants and revocations are all measured against it.</li>
 <li>Review evidence is always a trio: dated listing → signed review → closed revocation tickets.</li>
 <li>Leavers are the highest-risk moment — same-day deprovisioning, validated by sampling.</li>
 <li>"MFA available" is not "MFA enforced"; only the tenant policy screenshot proves enforcement.</li>
 <li>Physical access is access management — the building appears in the audit too.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ PART II · CH 4 — OPERATIONAL SECURITY ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="soc2-d4">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · Chapter Four</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Operational Security —<br>Watching and Responding</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">SECOPS-001 to SECOPS-008 cover the live battlefield: monitoring what's happening on our organization's systems (SIEM), keeping malware out (antivirus / EDR / IPS), and responding properly when something slips through. Two of our organization's 2024 exceptions — incident logging and system monitoring — live here, so this domain is personal.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">SIEM &amp; log monitoring</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Incident response</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Antivirus &amp; EDR</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Intrusion prevention</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Incident closure</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Detection: If You Can't See It, You Can't Stop It</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">CC7 asks two blunt questions: <em>would you notice an attack?</em> and <em>what would you do next?</em> The noticing half is SECOPS-001 (SIEM — security information and event management). A SIEM is essentially a funnel: servers, firewalls, endpoints and cloud services all stream their logs into one place, correlation rules look for patterns ("five failed logins then a success, from a new country"), and alerts page a human. The evidence is the funnel working: dashboards, alert reports, retention settings, and — crucially — <strong>proof that alerts were investigated</strong>, not just generated.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">The protection layer is three overlapping nets. <strong>Antivirus</strong> (SECOPS-004/005) catches known malware by signature — its evidence is console reports showing every endpoint covered and signatures updating automatically. <strong>EDR</strong> (SECOPS-006, endpoint detection &amp; response) watches <em>behaviour</em> — a Word document spawning PowerShell — and can isolate a machine remotely. <strong>IPS</strong> (SECOPS-007, intrusion prevention) sits on the network edge dropping hostile traffic. Auditors check the same three things for each: deployed everywhere? actually on? someone reading the alerts?</p>

 <div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Real real-world scenario — NC #22 and #24</div>
 In 2024 the auditor found incidents were being handled by chat and memory: no definition of what counts as a "security incident", no reporting form, no log (NC #22). Separately, system monitoring and patch tracking had no documented process or log templates (NC #24). The remediation cast tells the story: Xavier drafted the incident definition document and reporting form; HR put them in the handbook and briefed every employee on <em>how</em> to report; IT built and now maintains the logs, identified what to monitor, and wrote the patch-management SOPs. Detection tooling was never the gap — the <em>paper trail around it</em> was.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Incident Lifecycle — and Its Paper Trail</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">A compliant incident travels six stations, each leaving an artifact. <strong>Report</strong>: anyone can raise one (form/email/ticket) — the register entry is born. <strong>Classify</strong>: severity and type assigned per the definition document. <strong>Respond</strong>: contain, eradicate, recover — actions logged in the ticket as they happen. <strong>Escalate</strong>: severe cases follow the escalation matrix; the escalation record proves the right people knew at the right time. <strong>Analyse</strong>: root cause analysis — not "user error" but the five-whys version. <strong>Close</strong> (SECOPS-008): corrective actions tracked to completion, closure signed off, lessons reviewed in the incident review meeting. The register is the index; the auditor samples three incidents and follows each through all six stations.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the phishing Friday</div>
 A finance officer reports a convincing invoice email at 16:40 on a Friday. What the auditor wants to see six months later: the register entry (16:52, severity 2), the EDR isolation log for the laptop that clicked, the password reset ticket, the escalation note to management, an RCA identifying the spoofed domain, a corrective action ("add lookalike-domain rule to mail filter") closed two weeks later, and the incident appearing in that quarter's review minutes. Total writing time during the event: maybe twenty minutes. Value at audit: one entire control demonstrated end-to-end.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Evidence Shelf — and How Each Item Is Made</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Evidence</th><th>How it's produced</th><th>Owner</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>SIEM dashboards &amp; alert reports</td><td>Periodic exports/screenshots with dates; monthly monitoring report summarising alerts → investigations → outcomes</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Log retention records</td><td>Configuration screenshot showing retention period matching policy</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Incident register &amp; tickets</td><td>One row per incident, born at report time; tickets carry the live response narrative</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>RCA reports</td><td>Written within days of closure using a fixed template; linked from the register</td><td>IT + the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>AV/EDR console reports</td><td>Monthly coverage export: all endpoints, agent healthy, signatures current; gaps become tickets</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>IPS configurations &amp; blocked-traffic reports</td><td>Quarterly rule review plus sampled reports proving the system blocks and someone looks</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Incident review minutes</td><td>Quarterly meeting walking open/closed incidents and trends; minutes by the documentation team, decisions by Management</td><td>the documentation team → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Closure sign-offs</td><td>Management signature confirming corrective actions verified — closes the loop the auditor samples</td><td>Mgmt</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: "No incidents this year — great news for the audit!"</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">An empty incident register doesn't read as "secure"; it reads as "nobody reports anything". Auditors expect a living process: phishing attempts, lost laptops, false alarms. Several small, well-documented incidents with clean closures is the <em>best</em> possible evidence. Zero entries invites the question the auditor already knows the answer to.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Chapter takeaways</div>
 <ol>
 <li>Detection evidence must show the full chain: log → alert → investigation → outcome.</li>
 <li>AV, EDR and IPS answer the same three audit questions: everywhere, enabled, attended.</li>
 <li>Every incident leaves six artifacts; write them during the event, when they're cheap.</li>
 <li>A populated incident register is a strength — silence is the red flag.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ PART II · CH 5 — CLOUD & NETWORK ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="soc2-d5">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · Chapter Five</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Cloud &amp; Network Security —<br>The Perimeter and the Plumbing</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Ten controls (CLOUD-001 to CLOUD-010) cover the infrastructure our organization's services actually run on: AWS logging, web application firewalls, DDoS protection, firewall rules, network segmentation, hardened configurations, capacity, time synchronisation, remote access and encryption in transit. This is the most technical chapter — but every control reduces to a configuration that can be screenshotted and a review that can be signed.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">CloudTrail logging</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">WAF &amp; Shield</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Firewall rules</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Segmentation</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Hardening baselines</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Capacity</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">NTP</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">SSL/TLS</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Cloud Doesn't Audit Itself</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">A common misconception: "we're on AWS, so Amazon handles security." The <strong>shared responsibility model</strong> says otherwise — AWS secures the data centres and hardware; everything our organization configures (IAM roles, security groups, logging, encryption) is our organization's problem, and therefore our organization's evidence. CLOUD-001 starts with the foundation: <strong>CloudTrail</strong>, AWS's flight recorder, capturing every API call — who created that server, who opened that port, who read that bucket. Evidence is the configuration (trail on, all regions, logs centralised, retention set) plus proof someone reviews the alerts.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">In front of our organization's applications sit two shields: the <strong>WAF</strong> (CLOUD-002) filtering hostile web requests — SQL injection, cross-site scripting — and <strong>AWS Shield</strong> (CLOUD-003) absorbing DDoS floods. Behind them, <strong>firewall rules</strong> (CLOUD-004) and <strong>network segmentation</strong> (CLOUD-005) implement a simple idea: the network is not one open room but a series of locked compartments. Production cannot be reached from the guest Wi-Fi; the database accepts connections only from the application tier. The network diagram is the map of those compartments — and yes, an out-of-date diagram is itself a finding, because it means nobody knows the real shape of the network.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the firewall rule nobody owns</div>
 During the quarterly ruleset review (CLOUD-004), IT finds rule #214: "allow any → 10.0.3.18:3389, added 2024, no ticket, no comment." Nobody remembers it; the server it pointed to was decommissioned. This is exactly what the review exists for — rules accrete like sediment, and each forgotten one is an open door. The review record shows rule #214 flagged, investigated, removed, and the change ticketed. One spreadsheet row; one closed attack path; one perfect piece of audit evidence.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Quiet Controls Everyone Forgets</h2>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>Hardening (CLOUD-006):</strong> every new server starts from a secure baseline — unnecessary services disabled, default passwords gone, settings matched to CIS benchmarks (an industry checklist of secure configurations). Evidence: the baseline document, benchmark scan reports, and remediation of drift. <strong>Capacity (CLOUD-007):</strong> SOC 2's Availability criterion asks whether our organization will notice it's running out of disk <em>before</em> customers do — dashboards, threshold alerts, and a capacity-planning note in management review. <strong>NTP (CLOUD-008):</strong> the sleeper control. If server clocks disagree, logs can't be correlated and forensic timelines collapse — auditors check that all systems sync to a common time source. <strong>TLS (CLOUD-010):</strong> certificates inventoried, renewals diarised, weak protocols (TLS 1.0/1.1) disabled — provable with a scan report. An expired certificate is the most public possible compliance failure: customers see it before the auditor does.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Evidence Shelf — and How Each Item Is Made</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Evidence</th><th>How it's produced</th><th>Owner</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>CloudTrail / logging configs</td><td>Console screenshots + retention settings; monthly check that trails are still on (attackers turn them off first)</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>WAF / Shield dashboards &amp; blocked-traffic reports</td><td>Periodic exports; rule reviews recorded with date and reviewer</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Firewall ruleset review records</td><td>Quarterly: export ruleset → annotate each rule (keep/remove/investigate) → sign → ticket the changes</td><td>IT → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Network &amp; segmentation diagrams</td><td>Updated on every architecture change; version-dated so the auditor sees freshness</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Hardening baseline + CIS scan reports</td><td>Baseline doc by IT; periodic benchmark scans; drift items tracked to closure</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Capacity & utilisation reports</td><td>Monitoring exports reviewed monthly; scaling decisions minuted</td><td>IT → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>NTP configuration records</td><td>Screenshots of time-sync settings across servers/devices, checked after any rebuild</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Certificate inventory &amp; TLS scan</td><td>Register of certs with expiry dates + renewal evidence; scan proving weak ciphers off</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: screenshots taken the week before the audit.</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">A Type II audit covers a <em>period</em> (e.g. twelve months). A configuration screenshot dated the week before fieldwork proves the control existed for one week. The calendar's monthly/quarterly screenshot cadence exists to lay a dated trail across the whole period — same effort, spread out, infinitely more convincing.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Chapter takeaways</div>
 <ol>
 <li>Shared responsibility: AWS secures the building; our organization's configurations are our organization's evidence.</li>
 <li>Firewall rules and access rights rot the same way — only scheduled reviews remove the sediment.</li>
 <li>Diagrams, baselines and certificate inventories must carry dates; freshness is part of the evidence.</li>
 <li>Spread configuration evidence across the audit period — Type II measures duration, not snapshots.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ PART II · CH 6 — VULNERABILITY & PATCH ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="soc2-d6">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · Chapter Six</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Vulnerability &amp; Patch Management —<br>Finding Holes Before Attackers Do</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Six controls (VULN-001, 004, 005, 006, 007, 008) form a single pipeline: scan for weaknesses, test them like an attacker would, fix what's found within deadlines, patch routinely so new holes close fast, and harden servers so fewer holes open at all. our organization knows this pipeline intimately — the missing annual VAPT was exception NC #37 in 2024.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">Vulnerability scans</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Penetration testing</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Remediation SLAs</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Patch management</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Critical patches</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Server hardening</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Scanning vs Testing — Two Different Animals</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">A <strong>vulnerability scan</strong> (VULN-001) is automated and frequent: a tool walks our organization's systems against a database of tens of thousands of known weaknesses and produces a severity-ranked list. It's broad, cheap, and shallow. A <strong>penetration test</strong> (VULN-004) is the opposite: a skilled human, engaged annually, tries to actually <em>chain</em> weaknesses into a break-in — the way a real attacker would. The scan asks "is the window unlatched?"; the pen test climbs through it and shows you a photo from inside. Auditors want both, because each catches what the other misses.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">Both feed the same downstream machine: the <strong>remediation tracker</strong> (VULN-005). Every finding gets a severity, an owner, and a deadline from the policy's SLA table — typically: critical 7–15 days, high 30, medium 90. The auditor's test is brutal and arithmetic: export the tracker, compute age for each open item, and flag everything past its SLA. "We were busy" is not a compensating control; a documented <em>risk acceptance signed by management</em> is.</p>

 <div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Real real-world scenario — NC #37, the missing VAPT</div>
 our organization's 2024 report noted no annual VAPT (vulnerability assessment and penetration testing) had been performed. The remediation showed the standard division of labour: Xavier researched and shortlisted vendors, IT set the scope and negotiated the final quotation, and IT commenced the testing. The lesson for 2026: the VAPT is now a calendar event with a lead time — vendor booked a quarter ahead, scope agreed in writing (the "rules of engagement"), report received, findings tracked, <em>retest certificate</em> obtained. The retest matters: a pen test report full of open criticals is worse evidence than no report at all.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Patching — The Unglamorous Control That Stops Real Attacks</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Most real-world breaches exploit vulnerabilities that had patches available for months. That's why VULN-006/007 exist. Routine patching runs on a rhythm: vendor releases → triage → test on a non-critical group → deploy in a maintenance window → verify via the compliance dashboard → chase the stragglers. <strong>Critical patches</strong> (VULN-007) get an emergency lane: out-of-band deployment with expedited approval, then a <em>rescan to prove the hole is actually closed</em> — deployment alone isn't verification, because patches fail silently. Failed-patch reports are themselves evidence: they prove our organization looks.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — patch Tuesday, audit Thursday</div>
 The auditor picks a critical CVE from eight months ago and asks: when did you learn of it, when was it patched, how do you know the patch took? A compliant answer takes four documents and five minutes: the vulnerability scan that flagged it (dated), the tracker row with severity and SLA, the deployment report from the patch tool, and the rescan showing it gone. A non-compliant answer takes three nervous days of log archaeology. The difference is not security — both companies may have patched the same week. The difference is the <em>tracker</em>.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Evidence Shelf — and How Each Item Is Made</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Evidence</th><th>How it's produced</th><th>Owner</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>Internal scan reports &amp; schedules</td><td>Scanner output saved per cycle (monthly/quarterly), with the schedule itself as evidence of regularity</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Pen test report + rules of engagement + retest</td><td>External vendor produces; the documentation team files report, tracker, and retest certificate; Management approves scope and accepts residual findings</td><td>IT + Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Remediation tracker &amp; aging report</td><td>One row per finding: severity, owner, SLA date, closure evidence link; aging exported monthly</td><td>IT + the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Risk acceptance records</td><td>For anything past SLA or unfixable: written rationale + compensating controls + management signature + review date</td><td>Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Patch policy &amp; deployment reports</td><td>Policy defines SLAs and windows; patch tool exports prove deployment; dashboard shows fleet compliance %</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Maintenance window &amp; failed-patch records</td><td>Change tickets for windows; failure reports with remediation follow-up</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Hardening standards &amp; CIS reports (VULN-008)</td><td>Baseline doc + periodic benchmark scans + drift remediation, change-managed</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: treating the pen test report as the finish line.</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">To an auditor the report is the <em>starting gun</em>. What they actually grade is what happened next: findings triaged within days, criticals closed within SLA, a retest proving closure, and the leftovers formally risk-accepted. A company that finds 40 issues and closes them beats a company that finds 4 and ignores them — visible response is the control.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Chapter takeaways</div>
 <ol>
 <li>Scans are broad and frequent; pen tests are deep and annual; auditors expect both.</li>
 <li>The remediation tracker with SLA aging is the domain's centre of gravity — keep it arithmetic-clean.</li>
 <li>Critical patches need deployment <em>plus rescan</em>; closure means verified, not shipped.</li>
 <li>Book the VAPT a quarter early — vendor lead time was exactly how NC #37 happened.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ PART II · CH 7 — BUSINESS CONTINUITY ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="soc2-d7">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · Chapter Seven</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Business Continuity —<br>Surviving the Bad Day</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Eight controls (BCM-001 to BCM-008) answer the Availability criterion's core question: when something breaks — a disk, a power line, a building — does our organization keep its promises to clients? The 2024 audit found exactly this gap: backups existed, but there was no documented policy and no proof restores actually worked (NC #50). This chapter is where "we have backups" becomes "we can prove recovery".</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">Backups</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Restore testing</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Disaster recovery</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Fire drills</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Environment &amp; power</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Multi-site readiness</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">The BCP</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Backups Are a Hypothesis. Restores Are the Proof.</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">BCM-001 covers the backup machine: automated schedules, success/failure logs, retention settings, alerts when a job fails, and a monthly review of all of it. But the industry is littered with companies that backed up faithfully for years and discovered — on the worst day — that the backups were corrupt, incomplete, or unrestorable. Hence BCM-002: <strong>periodic restore tests</strong>. Pick a real system, restore it to a sandbox, time the process, screenshot the recovered data, and record whether it met the <strong>RTO</strong> (recovery time objective — how fast must we be back?) and <strong>RPO</strong> (recovery point objective — how much data may we lose?). Those two numbers turn vague hope into measurable promises.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">BCM-003 scales the same idea to a full <strong>disaster recovery test</strong>: not one database, but a scenario — "the primary AWS region is gone" — with failover executed, escalations exercised, gaps logged, and a corrective action list. BCM-007 asks whether our organization's geography helps or hurts: alternate sites, redundant connectivity, and dependency analysis. And BCM-008, the <strong>Business Continuity Plan</strong>, is the binder that ties it together: impact analysis, recovery strategies, contact trees, and communication procedures — reviewed annually, trained annually, and approved by management.</p>

 <div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Real real-world scenario — NC #50</div>
 The 2024 finding wasn't "our organization has no backups". It was sharper: our organization <em>couldn't demonstrate</em> a documented backup and restore process. The the documentation team's first remediation task was simply writing the policy that matched what IT already did — schedules, retention, responsibilities, test cadence. This is the most common SOC 2 lesson in miniature: the practice existed; the control didn't, because a control is practice <em>plus</em> paper <em>plus</em> proof.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Physical World Audits Too</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Three controls live in the building, not the cloud. <strong>BCM-004 — fire drills:</strong> conducted, attended, photographed, and reviewed, with observations ("stairwell B blocked") turned into corrective actions. <strong>BCM-005 — environment:</strong> temperature and humidity logs for equipment rooms, HVAC maintenance, fire detection tests, CCTV and access logs — Admin's quiet empire of checklists. <strong>BCM-006 — power:</strong> UPS and generator inspections, battery health, fuel checks, and an actual periodic test under load. The 2024 "Other" list already flagged power backup for access systems; BCM-006 generalises it. Auditors love these controls because they're unfakeable: either the generator log has monthly entries in different pens and dates, or it doesn't.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the restore test worth gold</div>
 Quarterly, IT restores the project database backup to an isolated server. This quarter it fails — the backup job had silently excluded a new schema added in March. <em>This is a successful test.</em> The failure is logged, the job fixed, the rescheduled test passes, and the whole arc — failure, fix, pass — goes in the report. To an auditor, that arc is more convincing than a year of unexamined green ticks: it proves the test is real and the team responds. Finding your disaster in a sandbox is the entire point of rehearsal.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Evidence Shelf — and How Each Item Is Made</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Evidence</th><th>How it's produced</th><th>Owner</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>Backup dashboards, job logs, schedules</td><td>Tool exports; monthly review note; failures ticketed with resolution</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Backup policy</td><td>the documentation team writes; defines scope, frequency, retention, test cadence, RTO/RPO; Management approves</td><td>the documentation team → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Restore test reports</td><td>Per test: scenario, steps, timing vs RTO/RPO, screenshots of recovered data, pass/fail, approver</td><td>IT → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>DR test plan, execution logs, gap tracker</td><td>Annual exercise; the documentation team scribes the timeline; gaps become corrective actions with owners</td><td>IT + the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Fire drill reports &amp; attendance</td><td>Admin schedules, runs, photographs; HR reconciles attendance; observations tracked</td><td>Admin + HR</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Environmental &amp; UPS/generator logs</td><td>Inspection checklists, AMC service reports, battery/fuel records — dated entries per visit</td><td>Admin</td></tr>
 <tr><td>BCP + BIA + contact lists</td><td>Xavier shapes the BIA/recovery strategy; the documentation team maintains the plan and version history; staff trained annually</td><td>Xavier + the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Management approvals &amp; review minutes</td><td>Annual BCP sign-off, DR results reviewed, budget decisions minuted</td><td>Mgmt</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: a beautiful BCP that nobody has opened since it was written.</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">Auditors test the plan's pulse, not its prose: when was it last reviewed, who was trained on it, do the phone numbers in the contact tree still work, did the last DR test reference it? A two-year-old approval date on the cover page converts a 60-page plan into a finding. The calendar's annual review-train-test cycle is what keeps it alive.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Chapter takeaways</div>
 <ol>
 <li>Backups prove intent; only restore tests prove capability. RTO/RPO turn promises into numbers.</li>
 <li>A failed restore test, documented and fixed, is premium evidence — rehearsal is for finding failures.</li>
 <li>The physical layer (drills, HVAC, UPS, generator) is Admin's domain and is judged by dated logbooks.</li>
 <li>The BCP must show a pulse: reviewed, trained, tested, and signed within the audit period.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ PART II · CH 8 — HR & SECURITY AWARENESS ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="soc2-d8">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · Chapter Eight</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">HR &amp; Security Awareness —<br>The Human Layer</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Eight controls (HRSEC-001 to HRSEC-008) recognise an uncomfortable statistic: most breaches start with a person, not a port. So SOC 2 audits the employee lifecycle itself — vetted on the way in, trained and bound by agreements while inside, cleanly disconnected on the way out. HR owns more evidence here than any other team, which surprises people who think compliance is an IT sport.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">Awareness training</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Orientation</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Acknowledgements</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Background checks</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Performance &amp; competency</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Exit process</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">NDAs</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Lifecycle, Audited</h2>
 <p class="fade-up"><strong>Before day one</strong> (HRSEC-004): background verification — identity, employment history, and for client-facing roles whatever the contract demands. The auditor samples new hires and asks for the report <em>dated before the start date</em>; a check completed three months into employment is a finding with a story attached. <strong>Day one</strong> (HRSEC-002/003): orientation covers policies, acceptable use, confidentiality and role-specific security duties <em>before system access is provisioned</em> — note how this control deliberately interlocks with IAM-006. The signed acknowledgement pack and NDA (HRSEC-008) are born here. <strong>Every year after</strong> (HRSEC-001): security awareness training — materials, schedule, attendance, quiz scores, and a chase list for the stragglers. <strong>Throughout</strong> (HRSEC-005/006): performance evaluations and a competency matrix proving people are qualified for the security responsibilities their roles carry. <strong>The last day</strong> (HRSEC-007): the exit checklist mirrors IAM-007 — access revoked, assets returned, NDA obligations reaffirmed, exit interview filed.</p>

 <div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Real real-world scenario — the awareness program built from scratch</div>
 NC #20 (2024): security awareness communication wasn't happening on any documented cadence. The remediation is a perfect case study in multi-team controls. Xavier designed a simple quarterly program and its content; the documentation team reviewed it with management; HR wove it into orientation; Management committed 3–5 minutes of every monthly all-hands to security; the Design Team produced the Dos &amp; Don'ts visuals; Admin put the posters on the walls; and the documentation team minutes the annual program review. Seven hands, one control — and every hand leaves a different artifact.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Why Auditors Take Training Seriously</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Awareness training looks soft next to firewalls, but it maps to CC1 (competence) and CC2 (communication) — and auditors treat it as a proxy for culture. Their favourite tests: pick five employees and find their completion records; pick the newest hire and check training happened during onboarding, not whenever; check the <em>content</em> was refreshed, because replaying a 2023 deck in 2026 signals box-ticking. Phishing simulations (HRSEC-001's sharpest evidence) add teeth: a campaign report showing click rates falling over time is the rare compliance artifact that doubles as a genuine security win.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the sampled leaver</div>
 The auditor picks a developer who resigned in November. The evidence pack that survives scrutiny: resignation letter (HR), exit checklist signed off the last working day (HR), access revocation tickets timestamped that afternoon (IT), laptop return record (Admin), NDA reaffirmation signature (HR), and exit interview note. Six artifacts, four teams, one afternoon. The pack that fails: "we emailed IT about it." The difference between the two is not effort on the day — it's whether the checklist <em>existed</em>.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Evidence Shelf — and How Each Item Is Made</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Evidence</th><th>How it's produced</th><th>Owner</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>Training materials &amp; schedule</td><td>Program content (Xavier-designed, management-reviewed) plus the annual calendar of sessions</td><td>Xavier + HR</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Attendance, completion &amp; quiz records</td><td>Sign-in sheets or LMS exports; completion tracked to 100% with documented chases</td><td>HR</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Phishing simulation reports</td><td>Campaign tool output: sent, clicked, reported — trended across quarters</td><td>IT + HR</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Acknowledgement &amp; NDA records</td><td>Signed during onboarding; tracker proves coverage incl. contractors and vendors (HRSEC-008)</td><td>HR</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Background verification reports</td><td>Vendor or internal check, filed and dated pre-start; exceptions need management approval</td><td>HR</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Performance &amp; competency records</td><td>Annual appraisal cycle artifacts; competency matrix mapped to job descriptions</td><td>HR → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Exit checklists &amp; interviews</td><td>One checklist per leaver, multi-team sign-offs, same-day timestamps</td><td>HR + IT + Admin</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: 100% training completion… of 80% of the staff.</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">The auditor reconciles training records against the <em>HR headcount list</em>, not against the training tool's own roster. Contractors, interns, mid-year joiners and the founder who "doesn't need it" are exactly who falls through. The fix is procedural: the completion tracker starts from HR's master list every cycle, and every gap has a dated chase or a documented exception.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Chapter takeaways</div>
 <ol>
 <li>SOC 2 audits the employee lifecycle: vetted in, trained and bound inside, cleanly cut off out.</li>
 <li>Sequence matters — orientation and acknowledgements come <em>before</em> access provisioning.</li>
 <li>Training evidence reconciles against HR's headcount, and content must visibly refresh each year.</li>
 <li>The exit pack is a four-team artifact; the checklist is what makes the afternoon survivable.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ PART II · CH 9 — DATA PROTECTION & PRIVACY ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="soc2-d9">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · Chapter Nine</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Data Protection &amp; Privacy —<br>The Chapter Still Being Written</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Eight controls (PRIV-001 to PRIV-008) sit in the calendar with their evidence columns still <em>empty</em> — the only domain in that state. That's not an oversight to hide; it's a to-do to understand. This chapter explains what the privacy domain demands, why it differs from security, and what evidence our organization will need to define before these controls can be audited.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">PRIV-001…008</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Privacy vs security</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Data lifecycle</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Evidence to be defined</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Privacy Is Not Security Wearing a Different Hat</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Security asks: <em>can unauthorised people get at the data?</em> Privacy asks a harder question: <em>even for authorised people, should this data have been collected, used this way, kept this long, or shared at all?</em> A perfectly secured database can still be a privacy violation — if the data inside was collected without consent, used beyond its stated purpose, or retained past its welcome. In SOC 2 terms, Security is the mandatory Common Criteria; <strong>Privacy is a separate Trust Service Criterion</strong> that a company opts into when its commitments (contracts, privacy policy, regulations like GDPR or your local jurisdiction's data protection regime) require it.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">The discipline runs on the <strong>data lifecycle</strong>: collect (with notice and lawful basis) → use (only for the stated purpose) → share (only with documented processors under contract) → retain (per schedule) → dispose (provably). Some of this machinery already exists in our organization's calendar under Risk &amp; Compliance: the DPIAs, data flow diagrams and data inventory (RISK-003), privacy policies and consent records (RISK-010), and the retention schedule and disposal records (RISK-011). The PRIV domain is where those threads will be woven into their own operating controls rather than borrowed ones.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — why this matters to a delivery company</div>
 our organization processes end-customer statement data for InfoIMAGE. Imagine a developer copies a production extract to a laptop "to debug faster". Security asks whether the laptop was encrypted (it was — see Disk Encryption, control 53). Privacy asks the questions that still sting: was that data <em>allowed</em> off production? Was the client's consent chain honoured? Is the copy now outside the retention schedule, undeletable on request? One convenient shortcut, three privacy exposures — none of them blocked by a firewall. The control that prevents it is a data-handling policy people actually know, plus a classification scheme that marks that extract "restricted".</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">What the Eight Controls Will Need</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">When the documentation team and Xavier populate this domain, expect the evidence lists to converge on a standard set: a <strong>privacy policy</strong> (external-facing) and <strong>data handling policy</strong> (internal); the <strong>record of processing activities</strong> — what personal data, whose, why, where, how long; <strong>consent and notice records</strong> where our organization is the controller, and <strong>data processing agreements</strong> where our organization is a processor for clients; <strong>data subject request procedures</strong> with a log proving requests are answered in time; <strong>cross-border transfer assessments</strong> for data moving between jurisdictions; <strong>privacy training records</strong>; and <strong>breach notification procedures</strong> wired into the incident process from Chapter Four — because a privacy breach starts a regulatory clock that ordinary incidents don't.</p>

 <div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Action for the documentation team</div>
 The empty Evidence Required cells in PRIV-001…008 are the calendar's only blank page — and an auditor reviewing the ISMS will eventually ask why. The pragmatic sequence: confirm with Xavier which privacy commitments our organization has actually made (client DPAs, the public privacy policy, applicable law), define the eight controls' scope from those commitments, then write the evidence lists in the same style as every other domain. Commitments first, controls second — privacy controls invented before reading the contracts tend to promise the wrong things.</div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Chapter takeaways</div>
 <ol>
 <li>Privacy governs <em>appropriateness</em> of data use; security only governs access. Both can fail independently.</li>
 <li>our organization already operates privacy machinery inside RISK-003/010/011 — PRIV will formalise it, not start from zero.</li>
 <li>The PRIV evidence columns are empty by design today; filling them starts from our organization's actual commitments.</li>
 <li>Privacy breaches carry notification deadlines — the incident process must know the difference.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ PART II · CH 10 — CHANGE MANAGEMENT ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="soc2-d10">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · Chapter Ten</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Change Management —<br>Nothing Reaches Production Unexamined</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Seven controls (CHG-001 to CHG-007) govern how anything — code, configuration, infrastructure — gets changed. For a software company like our organization this is the domain closest to daily work, which makes it both the easiest to evidence (the tools already log everything) and the easiest to violate (one "quick fix" straight to production). CC8 is the auditor's lens: changes are authorised, tested, approved, and traceable.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">Change requests &amp; CAB</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Emergency changes</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Deployments</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">SDLC</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Secure coding</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">App security testing</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Configuration mgmt</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Standard Path — and the Emergency Lane</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">CHG-001 defines the normal route: a change is <em>requested</em> (ticket), <em>assessed</em> (impact, risk, rollback plan), <em>approved</em> (CAB — the change advisory board, which in a company our organization's size is usually a short weekly meeting or an approval workflow, not a committee with biscuits), <em>tested</em>, <em>deployed</em> in a window, and <em>reviewed</em>. CHG-002 accepts reality: sometimes production is on fire and the fix can't wait for Tuesday. Emergency changes get an expedited lane — but not a lawless one: retroactive approval within a defined period, the risk assessed even if briefly, and a post-implementation review. The auditor's sharpest test here is <em>volume</em>: if 40% of changes are "emergencies", the normal process is fiction.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">The thread running through CHG-003/004 is <strong>segregation of duties</strong>: the person who writes a change should not be the only person who approves and deploys it. In a small team this is solved with tooling, not headcount — branch protection requiring a second reviewer, deploy pipelines that demand an approval click from someone other than the author. The "Segregation of Duties Validation Records" in the evidence lists are exactly those settings, screenshotted, plus samples proving no one self-merged to production.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — the auditor samples a deployment</div>
 From the release log the auditor picks deployment #312 and asks for its biography. The compliant answer is a chain of links our organization's tools already forged: Jira ticket (the request and approval) → pull request (code review by a second engineer) → CI pipeline run (tests green, SAST scan clean) → UAT sign-off (CHG-004) → deployment approval → deploy log → post-deployment check. Nobody created that chain "for compliance" — it's the normal engineering workflow. The only compliance work is ensuring the links never break: every deploy traces to a ticket, every merge has a non-author reviewer. Change management is the domain where good engineering hygiene <em>is</em> the control.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">Building Security In — SDLC, Secure Coding, Testing</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">CHG-004 asks for a documented SDLC: requirements → design → build → test → UAT → release, with security checkpoints at each gate (our organization's 2024 audit already verified SDLC policy, project plans and UAT sign-off as working controls — this calendar keeps them warm). CHG-005 narrows to the code itself: secure coding standards, mandatory peer review, SAST (static analysis scanning code for vulnerability patterns) wired into the pipeline, and developer security training. CHG-006 attacks from outside: DAST and application penetration testing against the running system, findings flowing into the same remediation tracker as Chapter Six. CHG-007 closes the loop on configuration: baselines approved, drift detected, unauthorised changes investigated — because an unticketed production change is either an undocumented fix or an intrusion, and the control's job is to notice <em>either</em>.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Evidence Shelf — and How Each Item Is Made</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Evidence</th><th>How it's produced</th><th>Owner</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>Change policy &amp; request tickets</td><td>the documentation team maintains the policy; every change lives as a ticket with risk/rollback fields filled</td><td>the documentation team + IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>CAB / approval records</td><td>Workflow approvals or short minutes; approver ≠ author, visibly</td><td>Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Emergency change records</td><td>Expedited tickets + retroactive approval + post-implementation review, all dated</td><td>IT → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Deployment &amp; release logs</td><td>Pipeline-generated; sampled against tickets to prove traceability</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Code review / PR logs</td><td>Repo settings screenshot (branch protection) + sampled PRs with reviewer identity</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>SAST/DAST reports &amp; remediation</td><td>Pipeline scan outputs; findings tracked with SLAs like any vulnerability</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>UAT sign-offs</td><td>Client or product-owner approval captured before release — already a proven our organization control</td><td>Mgmt + IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Config baselines &amp; CMDB records</td><td>Approved baselines, infrastructure-as-code history, drift alerts investigated</td><td>IT</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Secure-development training records</td><td>HR tracks completion for engineering staff annually</td><td>HR</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: the hotfix that skipped the ticket "just this once".</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">Configuration monitoring (CHG-007) will surface it, or the auditor's reconciliation of deploy logs against tickets will. Either way the finding isn't really about that fix — it's that the auditor can no longer trust the completeness of the change population, which poisons sampling across the whole domain. The two-minute ticket, even raised after the fact through the emergency lane, is what keeps the population clean.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Chapter takeaways</div>
 <ol>
 <li>Every change needs a biography: request → approval → test → deploy → review, all linked.</li>
 <li>The emergency lane is legitimate — but it has paperwork too, and its volume is itself audited.</li>
 <li>Segregation of duties is solved with branch protection and pipeline approvals, not extra staff.</li>
 <li>An unticketed production change is indistinguishable from an intrusion; that's why drift detection exists.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ══════════ PART II · CH 11 — AUDIT & CONTINUOUS MONITORING ══════════ -->
<section class="chapter" id="soc2-d11">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Part Two · Chapter Eleven</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Audit &amp; Continuous Monitoring —<br>The Domain That Audits the Others</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The final eight controls (AUDIT-001 to AUDIT-008) are meta: they don't secure a system, they secure the <em>evidence machine itself</em>. A central repository where artifacts land all year, quality checks before anything reaches an auditor, internal control testing, CAPA discipline, exception management, and dashboards that watch compliance continuously. For the documentation team, this chapter is the job description.</p>
 <div class="chapter-topics">
 <span class="topic-pill">Evidence repository</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Evidence validation</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Control testing</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">CAPA</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Exceptions</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Findings closure</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Compliance dashboards</span>
 <span class="topic-pill">Sampling readiness</span>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Evidence Repository — One Shelf, Not Forty Inboxes</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">AUDIT-001 establishes the single place where every artifact from Chapters One through Ten accumulates: a structured folder tree (or GRC tool) organised by control ID, with naming conventions, access restrictions, and submission logs. The difference it makes is brutal in practice. In 2024-style audit prep, evidence is excavated from inboxes and chat threads during fieldwork — slow, incomplete, and visibly improvised. With AUDIT-001 working, the monthly rhythm is: artifact is created → filed under its control ID within days → ticked on the evidence tracker. Audit week becomes a guided tour instead of an archaeology dig.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">AUDIT-002 adds the quality gate: before anything is handed over, someone checks it against a validation checklist — dated? in-period? system-generated where required? approver visible? complete population, not a flattering subset? This is the same review an auditor performs, run in advance by friendlier eyes. AUDIT-008 prepares for the auditor's favourite move, <strong>sampling</strong>: population reports (all joiners, all changes, all incidents) must be exportable and complete, because the auditor selects <em>their</em> sample from <em>your</em> population — and a population that omits records is a worse finding than a failed sample item.</p>

 <div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario — testing your own controls (AUDIT-003)</div>
 Quarterly, the documentation team plays auditor for one slice of the ISMS. This quarter: offboarding. They pull the leaver list from HR (population), pick three names (sample), and walk the evidence: checklist? revocation tickets? timestamps within policy? One leaver's VPN account survived nine days. That becomes an exception in the log, a CAPA with an owner and date (AUDIT-004), a fix (offboarding workflow now auto-creates the VPN task), and a retest next quarter proving it. When the external auditor later finds the same nine-day gap, the story has already changed from "undetected failure" to "detected, remediated, retested" — which is the difference between a control failure and a control <em>working</em>.</div>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">CAPA, Exceptions, and Findings — Three Logs That Keep our organization Honest</h2>
 <p class="fade-up">Three registers do the heavy lifting. The <strong>CAPA tracker</strong> (AUDIT-004): every finding — internal test, external audit, incident RCA — becomes a corrective (fix the instance) and preventive (fix the cause) action, with root cause, owner, target date, closure evidence, and management review of the aging. The <strong>exception tracker</strong> (AUDIT-005): when our organization knowingly deviates from policy ("legacy server can't take MFA until Q3"), the deviation is documented, risk-assessed, compensated, management-approved and time-boxed — turning a would-be finding into a governed decision. The <strong>findings tracker</strong> (AUDIT-006): the 2024 exceptions and everything since, tracked to verified closure. Together they prove the system <em>learns</em> — which is what CC4 (monitoring) actually asks.</p>
 <p class="fade-up">AUDIT-007 is the always-on layer: dashboards aggregating control health — training completion, patch compliance, open CAPAs, backup success — reviewed monthly so drift is caught in weeks, not at year-end. Continuous monitoring is what makes the second year of SOC 2 <em>cheaper</em> than the first: surprises shrink, fieldwork shortens, and the evidence is already on the shelf.</p>

 <h2 class="section fade-up">The Evidence Shelf — and How Each Item Is Made</h2>
 <div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table>
 <thead><tr><th>Evidence</th><th>How it's produced</th><th>Owner</th></tr></thead>
 <tbody>
 <tr><td>Evidence repository &amp; submission logs</td><td>Controlled folder/GRC structure by control ID; filing logged; access restricted</td><td>the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Validation checklist &amp; quality reviews</td><td>Xavier defines the checklist; the documentation team applies it before any handover</td><td>Xavier + the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Control test reports &amp; walkthroughs</td><td>Quarterly self-tests: procedure, population, sample, result — filed like an auditor's workpapers</td><td>Xavier + the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>CAPA tracker</td><td>Living register; every entry carries root cause, owner, date, closure evidence; aging reviewed by management</td><td>the documentation team → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Exception / risk-acceptance records</td><td>Standard form: deviation, risk, compensating control, approval, expiry; reviewed at each management review</td><td>Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Findings tracker &amp; closure evidence</td><td>External and internal findings tracked to retested closure with sign-off</td><td>the documentation team → Mgmt</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Compliance dashboards / KPI-KRI reports</td><td>IT automates feeds where possible; monthly snapshot filed; trends discussed in management review</td><td>IT + the documentation team</td></tr>
 <tr><td>Population reports &amp; traceability matrix</td><td>System exports proving completeness; matrix mapping every control → its evidence locations</td><td>IT + the documentation team</td></tr>
 </tbody>
 </table></div>

 <div class="myth-box fade-up">
 <div class="myth-myth">Trap: treating audit prep as a season.</div>
 <div class="myth-reality">If compliance work spikes every spring, the controls don't operate — they perform. Auditors detect seasonality instantly: file dates clustered in the month before fieldwork, trackers with one giant update, minutes written in batches. The entire point of the ISMS Calendar — and of this domain in particular — is to flatten that spike into a boring, sustainable monthly rhythm. Boring is the goal. Boring passes audits.</div>
 </div>

 <div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Chapter takeaways — and the close of Part II</div>
 <ol>
 <li>One repository, filed continuously, beats forty inboxes excavated annually.</li>
 <li>Validate evidence with the auditor's own questions before the auditor asks them.</li>
 <li>Self-testing converts undetected failures into detected-and-fixed ones — a categorically better audit story.</li>
 <li>CAPA, exceptions and findings are the proof that our organization's ISMS learns; dashboards prove it watches.</li>
 <li>Across all eleven domains the pattern never changed: activity → artifact → approval → shelf. Master that loop and SOC 2 stops being an event and becomes a habit.</li>
 </ol>
 </div>
 </div>
</section>

