<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m1">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 1</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Welcome &amp; the<br>Threat Landscape</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Your orientation: what information security means, why the threat is real and rising, and how to use this handbook.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Explain in one sentence what information security is, name the three threats it defends against, and describe why a single employee can be the difference between a non-event and a breach.</p></div><p class="fade-up">Welcome to our security awareness handbook. This is not a policy you skim and forget &mdash; it is a practical field guide to the threats you will actually meet, written so that anyone who uses a laptop and email at work can follow it. Work through it at your own pace; each module takes a few minutes and ends with the points worth remembering.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">What information security actually is</h2><p class="fade-up"><strong>Information security</strong> is the practice of protecting our systems, devices and data from theft, damage, snooping or disruption &mdash; whether the threat comes from a criminal on the other side of the world, a piece of malware, or an honest slip by a colleague. Strip away the jargon and it protects three things, every time: <em>secrecy, accuracy, and uptime</em>. (You will meet these as the CIA Triad in the next module.)</p><h2 class="section fade-up">The threat landscape &mdash; why this is not optional</h2><p class="fade-up">Cyber attacks are no longer rare or aimed only at banks. They are industrialised, automated, and indiscriminate: phishing kits are sold like software, ransomware gangs run help desks, and attackers scan the entire internet looking for one unlocked door. The uncomfortable truth from every industry report is the same &mdash; the large majority of breaches involve a <strong>human element</strong>: a clicked link, a reused password, a file sent to the wrong place.</p><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Why you, specifically, matter</div><p>Firewalls, antivirus and spam filters stop the easy, noisy attacks. The dangerous ones are quiet and aimed at <strong>people</strong> &mdash; a convincing email, a phone call from “IT support”, a USB stick left in the lift. No tool catches all of these. A single alert person who pauses and clicks “report” instead of “open” can stop an attack that every system missed. That is why you are described, accurately, as the <strong>first line of defence</strong>.</p></div><h2 class="section fade-up">What this handbook covers</h2><p class="fade-up">We move from foundations (the core ideas and how our organization is organised to manage risk), through the threats and how to defend against them (social engineering, phishing, malware, data leakage), into how we respond when something goes wrong, and finally the everyday habits and responsibilities that make all of it real. Bonus modules give you scenario challenges and a glossary you can keep coming back to.</p><div class="callout navy fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Where SOC 2 fits</div><p>This training is a requirement of our <strong>SOC&nbsp;2</strong> program &mdash; the independent attestation that proves to clients we handle their data responsibly. Completing it, and acting on it, is part of how our organization wins and keeps the trust that wins us work.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> If our antivirus and firewall are good, why does the company still need every employee trained?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Because the most damaging attacks deliberately target people, not machines &mdash; phishing, pretexting and social engineering walk straight past technical controls. Trained people are the control that catches what software cannot.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Information security protects three things: secrecy (confidentiality), accuracy (integrity) and uptime (availability).</li><li>Most breaches involve a human element &mdash; which means most are preventable by people.</li><li>Technology stops the easy attacks; you stop the clever ones.</li><li>This handbook is a SOC 2 requirement and a practical field guide, not box-ticking.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: title &amp; introduction slides 1&ndash;3</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m2">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 2</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">The CIA Triad</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The three-word foundation of all information security &mdash; and a test you can apply to any situation.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Define confidentiality, integrity and availability; give a our organization example of each; and use the triad as a test for whether something is a security issue.</p></div><p class="fade-up">If you remember only one model from this entire handbook, make it this one. Security people call it the <strong>CIA Triad</strong> &mdash; nothing to do with spies. It is the three promises we make about every piece of information we hold, and every control in this course exists to protect at least one of them.</p><div class="tsc-strip fade-up"><div class="tsc-item security"><div class="tsc-abbr">C</div><div class="tsc-name">Confidentiality</div><div class="tsc-desc">Only the right people can see it</div></div><div class="tsc-item integrity"><div class="tsc-abbr">I</div><div class="tsc-name">Integrity</div><div class="tsc-desc">It stays accurate &amp; untampered</div></div><div class="tsc-item availability"><div class="tsc-abbr">A</div><div class="tsc-name">Availability</div><div class="tsc-desc">It is there when we need it</div></div></div><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Pillar</th><th>What it means</th><th>A our organization example</th><th>How we protect it</th><th>What breaks it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Only authorised people can see the data</td><td>a personal-data database, a colleague salary</td><td>Access controls, encryption, need-to-know</td><td>A leaked file, a shared password</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Data stays accurate and is not secretly changed</td><td>A payment figure, an audit log, source code</td><td>Version control, approvals, checksums, backups</td><td>A tampered record, an unreviewed change</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Authorised users can reach it when needed</td><td>A live government portal we operate</td><td>Redundancy, backups, monitoring, DDoS defence</td><td>An outage, ransomware, a deleted backup</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Picture it &mdash; an online banking app</div><p><strong>Confidentiality:</strong> only you see your balance. <strong>Integrity:</strong> the balance is correct and has not been altered. <strong>Availability:</strong> the app works when you need to pay. Knock out any one of the three and customers lose trust instantly. That is why all three matter equally.</p></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Use the triad as a test</div><p>Not sure whether something counts as a “security issue”? Ask: <em>does it threaten confidentiality, integrity, or availability?</em> A document emailed to the wrong person threatens confidentiality. A spreadsheet someone edited without approval threatens integrity. A server nobody can reach threatens availability. If the answer is yes to any, treat it as a security matter and report it.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> A developer quietly changes a production figure without a review or record. Which part of the triad is threatened?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Integrity &mdash; the data may no longer be accurate or trustworthy, and there is no record of who changed it or why. (It may also touch confidentiality and availability, but integrity is the direct hit.)</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>C-I-A: Confidentiality (right people only), Integrity (accurate &amp; untampered), Availability (there when needed).</li><li>Every security control exists to protect at least one of the three.</li><li>Breaching any one &mdash; a leak, a forged record, or downtime &mdash; destroys client trust.</li><li>When unsure if something is a security issue, run it through the CIA test.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: CIA Triad slide 4</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m3">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 3</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Security Objectives<br>&amp; the ISMS</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Why we run a security program, and how an ISMS &mdash; backed by SOC 2 &mdash; keeps it consistent and provable.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Describe what an ISMS is, state our organization&#39;s core security objectives, and explain how SOC 2 and ISO 27001 relate.</p></div><p class="fade-up">If the CIA Triad is <em>what</em> we protect, our <strong>objectives</strong> are <em>why</em>, and the <strong>ISMS</strong> is <em>how</em> we organise the effort so it is deliberate and provable rather than accidental.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">Our security objectives</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Objective</th><th>In plain terms</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Safeguard assets</td><td>Protect client, financial and intellectual property from breach and loss</td></tr><tr><td>Protect trust</td><td>Prevent incidents that damage client confidence and our brand</td></tr><tr><td>Stay compliant</td><td>Meet our legal, contractual and SOC&nbsp;2 obligations and avoid penalties</td></tr><tr><td>Limit damage</td><td>Minimise disruption and financial loss when something does go wrong</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">What an ISMS is</h2><p class="fade-up">An <strong>Information Security Management System (ISMS)</strong> is simply the organised set of policies, procedures and controls we use to manage security risk <em>on purpose</em> &mdash; rather than reacting to fires. It is built on a continuous loop: assess the risks, put controls in place, check they work, and improve. Your everyday habits are the visible, auditable proof that this system is real.</p><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">SOC 2 and ISO 27001 &mdash; how they fit</div><p>You will hear both names. <strong>ISO&nbsp;27001</strong> is the international standard that describes how to build an ISMS. <strong>SOC&nbsp;2</strong> is the attestation our clients ask for &mdash; independent proof that our controls actually operate. Think of the ISMS as the engine and SOC&nbsp;2 as the inspection certificate that tells clients the engine runs. For this training, SOC&nbsp;2 is our headline commitment. (Each has its own booklet on the home page.)</p></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Why the rules are not arbitrary</div><p>Every rule you will follow &mdash; strong passwords, locking your screen, reporting odd emails &mdash; maps to a documented control that an auditor will test. When you follow them, you are literally generating the evidence that keeps our organization certified.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> A client asks for &lsquo;proof your security works.&rsquo; Do we hand them our ISO 27001 certificate, our SOC 2 report, or both, and what is the difference?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Both are valid. The ISO 27001 certificate says an accredited body confirmed our ISMS meets the standard; the SOC 2 report is a detailed description, written by auditors, of how our controls were designed and operated over a period. Certificate = badge; report = the full story.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Objectives: protect assets, protect trust, stay compliant, limit damage.</li><li>An ISMS manages security risk deliberately through a continuous assess-control-check-improve loop.</li><li>ISO 27001 describes the ISMS; SOC 2 independently proves it works &mdash; SOC 2 is our headline.</li><li>Your daily habits are the auditable evidence the controls are real.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Key Objectives &amp; ISMS slides 5&ndash;6</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m4">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 4</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Information<br>Classification &amp; Handling</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Four labels that tell everyone how carefully to handle each piece of information &mdash; and the rules for each.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Classify any piece of information into one of four levels and apply the correct handling, sharing, storage and disposal rules for that level.</p></div><p class="fade-up">Not all information needs the same protection. A press release and a personal-data database both matter, but you would guard them very differently. <strong>Classification</strong> gives everyone a shared language for how carefully to treat each thing &mdash; and it is the backbone of confidentiality.</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Level</th><th>Who can see it</th><th>our organization examples</th><th>Handling rule</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong style="color:var(--green)">Public</strong></td><td>Anyone</td><td>Website content, social posts, brochures</td><td>Freely shareable &mdash; but only the owner may publish</td></tr><tr><td><strong style="color:var(--mid)">Internal</strong></td><td>Employees &amp; authorised staff</td><td>Internal announcements, staff policies, team plans</td><td>Keep inside our organization; do not post externally</td></tr><tr><td><strong style="color:var(--gold)">Confidential</strong></td><td>Named, authorised people only</td><td>Strategic plans, passwords, client deliverables</td><td>Share strictly on need-to-know; encrypt in transit</td></tr><tr><td><strong style="color:var(--red)">Restricted</strong></td><td>A small, named group</td><td>Litigation documents, the most sensitive personal data</td><td>Highest protection; access logged; never copied casually</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">The handling lifecycle</h2><p class="fade-up">Classification is not just a label &mdash; it drives how data is <strong>handled, shared, stored and destroyed</strong> across its whole life:</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Confidential / Restricted rule</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Label</td><td>Mark documents with their level so others know how to treat them</td></tr><tr><td>Share</td><td>Need-to-know only; verify the recipient; use approved channels, never personal email</td></tr><tr><td>Store</td><td>Approved systems only; encrypted; not on personal devices or USB drives</td></tr><tr><td>Dispose</td><td>Shred printed copies in secure bins; delete digital copies through approved means</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The rule of thumb</div><p>When in doubt, treat information as <strong>more</strong> sensitive, not less &mdash; it is far cheaper to over-protect a public file than to under-protect a confidential one. And never downgrade a classification or widen who can see something without the owner&#39;s say-so.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> You are about to email a client deliverable to a partner firm from your personal Gmail because the office VPN is slow. What is wrong, and what should you do?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> A client deliverable is Confidential &mdash; it must move only through approved our organization channels, encrypted, to a verified recipient. Personal email is off-limits. Wait for the VPN or use the approved file-sharing system; if blocked, ask IT rather than working around the control.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Four levels, rising sensitivity: Public, Internal, Confidential, Restricted.</li><li>Confidential and Restricted move on need-to-know only, through approved channels.</li><li>Classification drives the whole lifecycle: label, share, store, dispose.</li><li>When unsure, protect at the higher level and check with the owner.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Information Classification slide 7</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m5">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 5</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Secure<br>Development</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">How our organization builds software that is safe by design &mdash; and why the review and testing gates exist.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Explain why security is built into development from the start, name the secure-coding principles, and describe how source code and secrets are protected.</p></div><p class="fade-up">our organization is, at heart, a software company &mdash; so much of our security is about building software that is safe by design. Even if you never write code, understanding this explains why certain steps cannot be skipped to hit a deadline.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">Why secure development matters</h2><p class="fade-up">A flaw caught in design costs almost nothing to fix; the same flaw caught after release &mdash; or after it is exploited &mdash; can cost a contract. Building security in from the start protects client and intellectual property, preserves confidence, keeps us aligned with SOC&nbsp;2 and ISO&nbsp;27001, and limits the blast radius of any breach.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">Security at every stage of the lifecycle</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Security activity</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Requirements</td><td>Risk assessment &mdash; what could go wrong, what must be protected</td></tr><tr><td>Design</td><td>Threat modelling and design review</td></tr><tr><td>Development</td><td>Secure coding + static analysis (scanning code for flaws)</td></tr><tr><td>Testing</td><td>Security testing, peer code review, dependency scanning</td></tr><tr><td>Deployment</td><td>Secure, correctly-configured environment; secrets kept out of code</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">Five secure-coding principles</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Principle</th><th>What it means in practice</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Security by design</td><td>Bake security in from day one, not as an afterthought</td></tr><tr><td>Least privilege</td><td>Code and users get the minimum access they need &mdash; nothing more</td></tr><tr><td>Fail securely</td><td>When something errors, do not leak sensitive details or fall open</td></tr><tr><td>Defence in depth</td><td>Layer protections (validation + authentication + encryption) so one failure is not fatal</td></tr><tr><td>Review &amp; test</td><td>Peer reviews plus automated static and dynamic analysis</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Protecting the source code itself</div><p>Our code is intellectual property. That means restricting who can read or write each repository, requiring review before code is merged, <strong>never committing passwords or secrets into code</strong>, and scanning regularly for accidentally-exposed credentials and known vulnerabilities. Secrets belong in a managed vault, not in a source file.</p></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Even if you do not write code</div><p>When a reviewer asks for a second look, or a deployment waits for a security check, that is the system working as intended &mdash; not red tape. The gate is what protects your work too.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> Under deadline pressure, a developer hard-codes a database password into the source to &lsquo;fix it later.&rsquo; Why is this dangerous even on a private repo?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Anyone with repo access &mdash; and anyone who ever gains it &mdash; now has the live credential, and it lives forever in the version history even if removed later. Secrets must go in a managed vault and be scanned for, never committed to code.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Security is built in at every stage &mdash; not bolted on at the end.</li><li>Five principles: security by design, least privilege, fail securely, defence in depth, review &amp; test.</li><li>Protect source code: restrict access, review before merge, never commit secrets, scan continuously.</li><li>Review gates and security checks protect us &mdash; they are not obstacles to rush past.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Secure Development slides 8&ndash;11</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m6">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 6</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">The Threat Landscape:<br>Attacks &amp; Actors</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Who is attacking, why, and the predictable stages of an attack &mdash; so you know where to break the chain.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Define a cyber attack, identify who attacks and why, and describe the typical stages of an attack so you can spot it early.</p></div><p class="fade-up">A <strong>cyber attack</strong> is any attempt to steal, damage or disrupt data or systems &mdash; by criminals, by malware, or even through human error. Before we study individual threats, it helps to know <em>who</em> is behind them and <em>how</em> a typical attack unfolds.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">Who attacks, and why</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Threat actor</th><th>Typical motivation</th><th>What it looks like for our organization</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Organised cybercrime</td><td>Money</td><td>Ransomware, payment fraud, stolen data sold on</td></tr><tr><td>Hacktivists</td><td>A cause or message</td><td>Defacement or disruption of a public system we run</td></tr><tr><td>Nation-state / espionage</td><td>Intelligence, advantage</td><td>Targeted intrusion against government data we hold</td></tr><tr><td>Malicious insiders</td><td>Grievance or gain</td><td>Data theft by someone who already has access</td></tr><tr><td>Careless insiders</td><td>No malice at all</td><td>Honest mistakes &mdash; the single biggest category</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">How an attack typically unfolds</h2><p class="fade-up">Most serious attacks follow a recognisable arc. Knowing it tells you where you can break the chain &mdash; usually right at the start.</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>What the attacker does</th><th>Where you can stop it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1. Recon</td><td>Researches targets (LinkedIn, the website, email formats)</td><td>Limit what you over-share publicly</td></tr><tr><td>2. Intrusion</td><td>Sends the phish, exploits a weak password or system</td><td>Pause before clicking; strong unique passwords + MFA</td></tr><tr><td>3. Foothold</td><td>Installs malware or steals credentials</td><td>Antivirus, patching, reporting anything odd</td></tr><tr><td>4. Escalation &amp; spread</td><td>Moves deeper, grabs more access</td><td>Least privilege limits how far they get</td></tr><tr><td>5. Impact</td><td>Steals data, deploys ransomware, disrupts service</td><td>Fast reporting shrinks the damage dramatically</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The reassuring part</div><p>Notice that nearly every stage can be broken by the same short list of habits: pause before you click, verify before you trust, keep software updated, use MFA, and report anything odd. The earlier the chain breaks, the smaller the damage.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>A cyber attack steals, damages or disrupts data or systems &mdash; including via human error.</li><li>Attackers range from organised crime to careless insiders &mdash; the last is the biggest category.</li><li>Attacks follow stages: recon, intrusion, foothold, escalation, impact.</li><li>You can break the chain at almost any stage, most cheaply at the start.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Cyber Attacks &amp; Threats slides 12&ndash;13</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m7">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 7</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Social Engineering &mdash;<br>Hacking the Human</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The number-one cause of real breaches: the psychology attackers exploit and the one habit that defeats them.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Recognise social engineering, name the psychological levers it pulls, identify the main attack types, and apply the universal defence.</p></div><p class="fade-up">This is the big one &mdash; the technique behind the majority of real breaches. <strong>Social engineering</strong> is hacking the <em>human</em> instead of the computer. The attacker poses as someone you trust and exploits very normal feelings to get you to hand over information or access.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">The levers they pull</h2><p class="fade-up">Social engineers are amateur psychologists. They reach for a small set of reliable triggers &mdash; learn to feel them as warning signs:</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Lever</th><th>How it is used against you</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Authority</td><td>&lsquo;This is the CEO / IT / the regulator&rsquo; &mdash; we comply with authority</td></tr><tr><td>Urgency</td><td>&lsquo;Act now or the account locks&rsquo; &mdash; pressure stops you thinking</td></tr><tr><td>Fear</td><td>&lsquo;You are in trouble unless&hellip;&rsquo; &mdash; fear overrides caution</td></tr><tr><td>Curiosity / greed</td><td>&lsquo;Free voucher&rsquo;, &lsquo;see who viewed your profile&rsquo; &mdash; temptation</td></tr><tr><td>Trust / liking</td><td>A friendly, familiar tone, or a spoofed colleague&#39;s name</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">The main forms of social engineering</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>How it works</th><th>Tell-tale sign</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Phishing</strong></td><td>Fake emails/sites that steal credentials or deliver malware</td><td>Unexpected link/attachment, odd sender (see next module)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Baiting</strong></td><td>Something tempting &mdash; a &lsquo;free&rsquo; download or a USB drive left lying around</td><td>Too-good-to-be-true offers; stray USB sticks</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Pretexting</strong></td><td>An invented backstory (&lsquo;I am from IT support&rsquo;) to coax out information</td><td>Unsolicited contact asking for credentials or details</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Tailgating</strong></td><td>Following an authorised person through a secure door</td><td>Someone without a badge close behind you</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Shoulder surfing</strong></td><td>Watching you type a password or PIN</td><td>Someone lingering near your screen or keypad</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The universal defence</div><p>Whatever the flavour, social engineering relies on you <em>not pausing to verify</em>. So pause. Confirm identity through a known, separate channel (call the person back on a number you already have). Do not plug in unknown USB drives. Do not hold secure doors for people you do not recognise. A moment of polite suspicion beats a breach.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> Someone calls saying they are from IT, knows your name and team, and needs your password to &lsquo;fix your mailbox urgently.&rsquo; What is happening and what do you do?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Classic pretexting + authority + urgency. Real IT never needs your password. Do not give it. Hang up and call IT back on the official number you already have. Then report the call so others are warned.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Social engineering attacks people, not machines &mdash; exploiting authority, urgency, fear, curiosity and trust.</li><li>Main types: phishing, baiting, pretexting, tailgating, shoulder surfing.</li><li>The shared weakness it exploits is you not pausing to verify.</li><li>Verify identity through a separate, known channel; never plug in stray USBs; never let strangers tailgate.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Social Engineering &amp; its types slides 14, 17&ndash;18</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m8">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 8</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Phishing,<br>Dissected</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Take apart a real phishing email, learn the seven red flags, and meet the targeted variants that carry no malware.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Dissect a phishing email, distinguish spear-phishing / whaling / business email compromise, and run the red-flag checklist on any message.</p></div><p class="fade-up">Phishing deserves its own module because it is the single most common way attackers get in. <strong>Phishing</strong> uses fake emails, messages or websites to trick you into giving up passwords or sensitive data, or into clicking a malicious link or attachment. The message looks legitimate &mdash; that is the entire craft.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">Anatomy of a phishing email</h2><p class="fade-up">Here is a realistic example, dissected. Train your eye on the seven red flags and you will catch the vast majority of phish.</p><div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Dissected: a phishing email</div><p style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:13px;line-height:1.7;"><strong>From:</strong> IT Support &lt;it-support@dsi-secure-helpdesk.com&gt; &nbsp;<span style="color:var(--red)">&#9312; look-alike domain, not our real one</span><br><strong>Subject:</strong> URGENT: Your mailbox will be deleted in 24 hours &nbsp;<span style="color:var(--red)">&#9313; fear + urgency</span><br><br>Dear User, &nbsp;<span style="color:var(--red)">&#9314; generic greeting</span><br>We deteced unusual activity on you account. &nbsp;<span style="color:var(--red)">&#9315; spelling/grammar errors</span><br>You must <u>verify your password</u> immediately or lose all email. &nbsp;<span style="color:var(--red)">&#9316; asks for credentials / unusual request</span><br><a>https://dsi-login.account-verify.ru/secure</a> &nbsp;<span style="color:var(--red)">&#9317; hover shows a strange real destination</span><br>Regards, The IT Team &nbsp;<span style="color:var(--red)">&#9318; no real name, no way to verify</span></p></div><h2 class="section fade-up">The seven red flags &mdash; your checklist</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Red flag</th><th>What to do</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Look-alike or wrong sender domain</td><td>Check the address carefully, character by character</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Urgency or threats</td><td>Slow down &mdash; pressure is the attacker&#39;s tool</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Generic greeting</td><td>Be wary of &lsquo;Dear User / Customer&rsquo;</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Spelling and grammar errors</td><td>Professional senders proofread; attackers often do not</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Asks for credentials or money</td><td>No legitimate party asks for your password by email</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Mismatched links</td><td>Hover to see the real destination before clicking</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>Unexpected attachments</td><td>Do not open files you were not expecting</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">The dangerous variants</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Variant</th><th>What is different</th><th>Why it is more dangerous</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Spear phishing</td><td>Personalised to you using real details</td><td>Far more convincing than bulk phishing</td></tr><tr><td>Whaling</td><td>Targets executives specifically</td><td>High access, high payoff</td></tr><tr><td>Business Email Compromise (BEC)</td><td>Impersonates a senior leader to request payments or gift cards</td><td>Costs companies billions; no malware to detect</td></tr><tr><td>Vishing / smishing</td><td>Phishing by phone call or SMS</td><td>Bypasses email filters entirely</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Your defence routine</div><p>Verify the sender. <strong>Hover over links</strong> to see where they really go. Never enter your password on a page you reached <em>from a link</em> &mdash; navigate there yourself. Enable <strong>MFA</strong> everywhere. And if a message pressures you to act <em>right now</em>, that pressure is itself the warning sign. When in doubt, report it &mdash; you will never be in trouble for a careful false alarm.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> An email &lsquo;from the CEO&rsquo; asks you to urgently buy gift cards for a confidential staff reward and send the codes. No malware, perfect logo. What is it and what do you do?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Business Email Compromise &mdash; authority + urgency + secrecy + unusual request. Do not buy anything. Verify with the CEO through a known channel (call, or message in our internal tool). Real executives welcome the check; report the email so others are warned.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Phishing is the most common intrusion method &mdash; learn to dissect the message.</li><li>Seven red flags: wrong domain, urgency, generic greeting, errors, credential/money requests, mismatched links, unexpected attachments.</li><li>Variants &mdash; spear phishing, whaling, BEC, vishing/smishing &mdash; are more targeted and often carry no malware to catch.</li><li>Never enter credentials from a link; navigate yourself, use MFA, and report anything suspicious.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Phishing &amp; phishing tactics slides 15&ndash;16</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m9">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 9</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Malware<br>&amp; Ransomware</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The malicious software that targets your device &mdash; the types, the symptoms, and how to keep it out.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Recognise the main malware types, understand ransomware, spot the symptoms of infection, and apply the prevention basics.</p></div><p class="fade-up"><strong>Malware</strong> (malicious software) is any program built to harm your device or network. It usually arrives the same few ways: a dodgy download, an infected attachment, a malicious link, or a stray USB drive.</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>What it does</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Virus</td><td>Attaches to a file and spreads when that file runs</td></tr><tr><td>Worm</td><td>Spreads by itself across a network, no user action needed</td></tr><tr><td>Trojan</td><td>Disguised as something useful; opens a back door once run</td></tr><tr><td>Ransomware</td><td>Encrypts your files and demands payment to unlock them</td></tr><tr><td>Spyware / keylogger</td><td>Secretly watches you and steals data and passwords</td></tr><tr><td>Adware / PUPs</td><td>Unwanted programs that degrade and expose your device</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">Ransomware &mdash; the one that shuts companies down</h2><p class="fade-up">Ransomware deserves special attention. It locks up your files (and often your colleagues&#39; too) and demands payment. Modern gangs also <em>steal</em> the data first and threaten to publish it &mdash; so backups alone are not a complete defence. The best protection is layered: do not let it in (phishing awareness, patching), limit its spread (least privilege), and recover fast (tested backups). <strong>Reporting the very first sign</strong> can stop it before it spreads across the network.</p><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Symptoms of infection</div><p>Your device suddenly runs slow; unusual pop-ups or messages appear; files or settings change on their own; programs you did not install show up; or files become inaccessible or renamed. If you see these &mdash; do not try to quietly fix it. Disconnect from the network if you can, and <strong>report it immediately</strong>.</p></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Prevention basics</div><p>Keep antivirus installed and updated; keep your operating system and apps <strong>patched</strong> (updates close the holes malware uses); do not download software or files from untrusted sources; do not plug in unknown USB drives; and think before every attachment and link.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> Your files suddenly have strange new extensions and a text note appears demanding Bitcoin. What are the first two things you should do?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> 1) Disconnect the device from the network (Wi-Fi/cable) to stop it spreading. 2) Report immediately to IT/security &mdash; do not pay, do not delete, do not keep working. Speed limits how far ransomware reaches.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Malware includes viruses, worms, trojans, ransomware, spyware and more &mdash; it arrives via downloads, attachments, links and USBs.</li><li>Ransomware encrypts (and often steals) data; layered defence + tested backups + fast reporting beat it.</li><li>Symptoms: slowness, pop-ups, self-changing files, unknown programs, locked files.</li><li>Prevent it: update antivirus, patch everything, avoid untrusted sources and stray USBs, and report early.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Malware slide 19</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m10">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 10</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Data Leakage<br>&amp; Shadow IT</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Sensitive data slipping out the side door &mdash; the everyday convenience decisions that cause it, and the safe alternatives.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Explain what data leakage is, list the common ways it happens, and choose the safe alternative every time.</p></div><p class="fade-up"><strong>Data leakage</strong> is sensitive information leaving our organization for somewhere it should not go. Crucially, most leaks are not dramatic hacks &mdash; they are <em>convenience decisions</em> by well-meaning people that go wrong.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">How leaks really happen</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>The leak</th><th>The safe alternative</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Uploading work files to a personal Google Drive or Dropbox to work from home</td><td>Use the VPN and our approved file storage</td></tr><tr><td>Emailing a client file to your personal account</td><td>Keep work files in approved systems and channels only</td></tr><tr><td>Copying confidential data to a USB stick or phone</td><td>Removable media is restricted and monitored &mdash; do not</td></tr><tr><td>Sharing a document link set to &lsquo;anyone with the link&rsquo;</td><td>Share to named people only, with the right permissions</td></tr><tr><td>Discussing client details in a public place or on social media</td><td>Treat client information as strictly confidential</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">Shadow IT &mdash; the quiet risk</h2><p class="fade-up">"+Q+"Shadow IT"+q+" is using unapproved apps and services for work &mdash; a personal cloud account, an unsanctioned chat tool, a free online PDF converter you upload a contract into. It feels harmless and helpful, but it moves company data outside everything we can protect, monitor or prove to an auditor. If you need a tool, ask IT to approve one rather than reaching for a personal account.</p><div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Why this matters so much at our organization</div><p>We hold customer and personal data under strict contracts. A single confidential file in the wrong cloud account can breach an NDA, fail a SOC&nbsp;2 control, and lose a client&#39;s trust permanently &mdash; even if no attacker was ever involved.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> You need to send a 200&nbsp;MB client dataset to a teammate and email rejects it, so you think about a free file-transfer website. Why is that risky and what should you do?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> A free site is shadow IT &mdash; the data leaves our control and may be stored or scanned by a third party, breaching confidentiality and possibly the client NDA. Use our organization-approved sharing system, or ask IT for the sanctioned way to move large files.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Data leakage is sensitive information escaping our organization &mdash; usually via convenience, not hacking.</li><li>Top vectors: personal cloud, personal email, USB drives, over-broad share links, loose talk.</li><li>Shadow IT (unapproved apps) moves data beyond our protection and proof &mdash; get tools approved.</li><li>Keep work data in approved systems; when blocked, ask IT instead of working around it.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Data Leakage slide 20</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m11">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 11</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Impact &amp; Common<br>Risk Factors</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">What a breach really costs our organization &mdash; and the everyday, fixable habits behind most incidents.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Describe the real business impact of a breach and identify the common, fixable risk factors behind most incidents.</p></div><p class="fade-up">It is tempting to think a breach is "+Q+"an IT problem."+q+" It is not &mdash; the fallout lands on the whole company, and for a firm whose business <em>is</em> trust, the reputational damage often hurts more than the immediate bill.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">What a breach actually costs</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Impact</th><th>What it looks like</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Reputation loss</td><td>Clients and partners lose confidence; future bids suffer</td></tr><tr><td>Financial loss</td><td>Incident response, downtime, fraud, lost revenue</td></tr><tr><td>Legal &amp; regulatory</td><td>Action for breaching data laws or contracts; penalties</td></tr><tr><td>Intellectual property loss</td><td>Source code, designs and know-how stolen</td></tr><tr><td>Client confidence</td><td>Existing contracts at risk; trust is slow to rebuild</td></tr><tr><td>Business interruption</td><td>Teams stop work; deadlines and SLAs missed</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">Common risk factors &mdash; and how to close them</h2><p class="fade-up">Most breaches come not from genius hackers but from ordinary, fixable habits. The good news: nearly every one is a <em>behaviour</em> you can change today, with no budget and no IT ticket.</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Risk factor</th><th>Your fix</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Reused passwords</td><td>Unique password per account + a password manager + MFA</td></tr><tr><td>Oversharing sensitive data</td><td>Need-to-know; approved channels only</td></tr><tr><td>Over-trusting tools</td><td>Stay alert &mdash; no antivirus or filter is 100%</td></tr><tr><td>Not reporting odd things</td><td>Report early; IT cannot see what you do not raise</td></tr><tr><td>Unlocked, unattended devices</td><td>Lock your screen every time you step away</td></tr><tr><td>Opening attachments blindly</td><td>Verify the sender, even known contacts, before opening</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The common thread</div><p>Look down that fix column &mdash; almost every entry is something <em>you</em> control. That is the empowering truth of this whole handbook: most risk is closed by everyday behaviour, not expensive technology.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> Why is reusing one strong password across accounts still dangerous, even if the password is genuinely strong?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Because if any one of those services is breached, attackers take your password and try it everywhere else (&lsquo;credential stuffing&rsquo;). One leak then unlocks all your accounts. Strength does not help if the password is reused &mdash; uniqueness does.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>A breach hits the whole business: reputation, finances, legal exposure, IP and client trust.</li><li>For our organization, lost client confidence often costs more than the incident itself.</li><li>Most risk factors are everyday habits: reused passwords, oversharing, unlocked devices, blind attachments, not reporting.</li><li>Because the gaps are behavioural, you can personally close most of them starting now.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Impact of Cyber Attack &amp; Common Risk Factors slides 21&ndash;22</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m12">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 12</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Incident Management<br>&amp; Response</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Spot the warning signs, understand the response lifecycle, and master the one action that is always yours: reporting.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Recognise the signs of a security incident, follow the response lifecycle at a high level, and &mdash; above all &mdash; report correctly and fast.</p></div><p class="fade-up">No matter how careful we are, incidents happen. What separates a minor scare from a major breach is how fast and how well we respond. A <strong>security incident</strong> is any event that may compromise the confidentiality, integrity or availability of our information or systems.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">Signs something may be wrong</h2><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Incident indicators</div><p>Repeated or unusual login attempts &middot; logins at odd hours or from unfamiliar places/devices &middot; access from two locations minutes apart &middot; malware or antivirus alerts &middot; files or settings changing on their own &middot; a colleague reporting an email &lsquo;from you&rsquo; that you never sent &middot; or simply a system behaving in a way that does not feel right.</p></div><h2 class="section fade-up">The response lifecycle</h2><p class="fade-up">You do not need to run this &mdash; specialists do &mdash; but understanding it shows why your one job (reporting) matters so much.</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Phase</th><th>What happens</th><th>Your part</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Prepare</td><td>Plans, tools and training are in place</td><td>Know how to report (this module)</td></tr><tr><td>Detect &amp; report</td><td>The incident is spotted and raised</td><td><strong>This is you</strong> &mdash; report immediately</td></tr><tr><td>Contain</td><td>Stop it spreading (isolate devices/accounts)</td><td>Follow instructions; do not interfere</td></tr><tr><td>Eradicate</td><td>Remove the cause (malware, access)</td><td>Provide details of what you saw</td></tr><tr><td>Recover</td><td>Restore systems safely to normal</td><td>Resume only when cleared</td></tr><tr><td>Lessons learned</td><td>Improve so it does not recur</td><td>Share honestly what happened</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Your single most important action: REPORT</div><p>The moment you suspect something &mdash; a phishing email, a lost laptop, a strange pop-up, a file you should not be able to open &mdash; <strong>report it immediately</strong> to your manager or IT/security. Early reporting, even if you are not sure, is never the wrong call. An attack caught in minutes is a non-event; the same attack caught in weeks is a crisis. You will never be in trouble for reporting in good faith.</p></div><div class="callout navy fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What NOT to do</div><p>Do not try to investigate or &lsquo;fix&rsquo; it yourself. Do not forward a suspected phishing email to colleagues (report it instead). Do not pay a ransom or reply to the attacker. Do not power-cycle or wipe a device before being told &mdash; valuable evidence can be lost. And do not stay silent out of embarrassment &mdash; that is what attackers count on.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> You clicked a link in a suspicious email and entered your password before realising. You feel embarrassed. What is the right move?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Report it right now, change your password immediately (from a known-good device), and enable/confirm MFA. Speed limits the damage &mdash; the embarrassment of reporting is tiny next to the cost of staying quiet while an attacker uses your account.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>An incident is any event threatening confidentiality, integrity or availability.</li><li>Watch for unusual logins, odd access patterns, malware alerts and systems behaving strangely.</li><li>Response runs prepare &rarr; detect/report &rarr; contain &rarr; eradicate &rarr; recover &rarr; learn.</li><li>Your job is to REPORT immediately &mdash; early reporting is always right; never investigate or hide it.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Incident Management &amp; Incident Response slides 23&ndash;24</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m13">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 13</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Real-World<br>Case Studies</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Three recent incidents, each tied back to a defence you have learned.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Draw concrete lessons from real incidents and connect each one back to a defence you now know.</p></div><p class="fade-up">Theory sticks better with real stories. Here are three recent incidents, each tied to a defence from this handbook.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">Case 1 &mdash; CEO impersonation (BEC), 2025</h2><p class="fade-up">An employee at a consulting firm received an email impersonating the CEO, sent from a throwaway address, asking them to buy Amazon gift vouchers for a "+Q+"confidential staff reward."+q+" Trusting the apparent authority, they bought the vouchers and shared the codes &mdash; straight to the attacker. The money was gone before anyone realised.</p><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What would have stopped it</div><p>Every red flag was present: authority (the CEO), urgency and secrecy, an unusual request (gift cards), and a wrong sender address. One verification call through a known channel ends the scam. <em>Defence: Module 8 &mdash; verify, never act on pressure alone.</em></p></div><h2 class="section fade-up">Case 2 &mdash; Flipkart denial-of-service, 2021</h2><p class="fade-up">The e-commerce giant was hit by a <strong>Denial-of-Service</strong> attack &mdash; servers flooded with traffic until services went offline and real customers were locked out. No data was necessarily stolen, but the disruption and reputational hit were real.</p><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The lesson</div><p>This one targets <strong>Availability</strong> &mdash; the &lsquo;A&rsquo; in CIA. Attacks are not only about stealing data; sometimes the goal is simply to take you offline. <em>Defence: Modules 2 &amp; 12 &mdash; resilience, monitoring and fast response.</em></p></div><h2 class="section fade-up">Case 3 &mdash; the reused-password breach (composite)</h2><p class="fade-up">A staff member used the same password for a personal site and their work account. The personal site was breached; attackers took the leaked password and tried it against corporate logins &mdash; and walked straight in, because there was no second factor. From there they read months of email before being noticed.</p><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What would have stopped it</div><p>A unique password and <strong>MFA</strong> would have stopped the reused credential cold. <em>Defence: Modules 11 &amp; 15 &mdash; unique passwords + MFA everywhere.</em></p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> Across these three cases, what single habit would have helped in all of them?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Pausing to verify and using basic safeguards: verify unusual requests (Case 1), monitor and respond fast (Case 2), and never reuse passwords while always using MFA (Case 3). The human pause plus MFA is the through-line.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Executive impersonation (BEC) weaponises authority, urgency and secrecy &mdash; verify through a known channel.</li><li>DoS attacks target availability, not data &mdash; resilience and fast response matter.</li><li>Reused passwords + no MFA let one leak unlock everything &mdash; unique passwords and MFA stop it.</li><li>Every real case ties back to a simple defence you now know.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Case Studies slides 25&ndash;28</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m14">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 14</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Data Protection<br>&amp; Sensitive Data</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Much of what we handle is personal data about real people &mdash; here is how to protect it properly.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Identify PII and sensitive data, apply the data-protection principles across the data lifecycle, and honour our organization&#39;s your local jurisdiction and SOC 2 obligations.</p></div><p class="fade-up">Much of what our organization handles is <strong>personal data</strong> about real people. Protecting it is both an ethical duty and a SOC&nbsp;2 commitment.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">PII and sensitive data</h2><p class="fade-up"><strong>Personally Identifiable Information (PII)</strong> is anything that can identify an individual &mdash; name, date of birth, address, email, phone, <strong>national ID number, passport number</strong>. Some data is <em>especially</em> sensitive (health, finances, biometrics) and needs the highest care. On its own or combined, PII can be used to impersonate or harm someone.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">The principles &mdash; and what they mean for you</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Principle</th><th>In practice</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Lawfulness &amp; consent</td><td>Process personal data only with a proper, informed basis</td></tr><tr><td>Purpose limitation</td><td>Collect it for a specific, legitimate reason &mdash; and only that</td></tr><tr><td>Data minimisation</td><td>Gather only what you actually need</td></tr><tr><td>Accuracy</td><td>Keep it correct and up to date</td></tr><tr><td>Storage limitation</td><td>Keep it only as long as needed, then dispose securely</td></tr><tr><td>Security</td><td>Protect it throughout its whole life</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">Protecting PII day to day</h2><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The handling habits</div><p>Treat all PII as sensitive. Share it on need-to-know only. Collect the minimum. Store it in approved, access-controlled systems. <strong>Dispose securely</strong> &mdash; shred printed PII, delete digital copies through approved means. Never move it to personal devices, personal email or unapproved cloud.</p></div><div class="callout navy fade-up"><div class="callout-label">your local jurisdiction &amp; our clients</div><p>Beyond SOC&nbsp;2&#39;s Confidentiality and Privacy criteria, we must respect the data-protection expectations of your local jurisdiction and of each client&#39;s jurisdiction and contract. When a project involves customer or personal data, follow the specific handling rules for that engagement &mdash; and ask your lead if anything is unclear.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> A teammate asks you to send the full sensitive personal dataset so they can &lsquo;test something quickly.&rsquo; They are on the project but do not need the real data for a test. What do you do?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Apply data minimisation and need-to-know: do not send real PII for a test. Offer anonymised or synthetic test data instead, through an approved channel. Sharing live PII without a genuine need breaches the principles &mdash; and possibly the client contract.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>PII is anything that can identify a person &mdash; name, national ID, passport, contact details and more.</li><li>Principles: lawful basis, purpose limitation, minimisation, accuracy, storage limitation, security.</li><li>Handle PII on need-to-know; collect the minimum; store in approved systems; dispose securely.</li><li>Honour SOC 2 Privacy/Confidentiality plus each client&#39;s and your local jurisdiction&#39;s requirements.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: PII &amp; Data Protection slides 29&ndash;31</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m15">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 15</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Everyday<br>Best Practices</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The practical habits &mdash; email, devices, passwords, remote, physical, social &mdash; that do most of the protecting.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Apply the everyday security habits across email, devices, passwords, remote work, physical space and social media &mdash; and understand why MFA and passphrases work.</p></div><p class="fade-up">This is where it all becomes practical. None of these habits are hard; the whole game is doing them <em>consistently</em>. Here they are, by area.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">Email</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Do</th><th>Avoid</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Open attachments only from trusted, expected senders</td><td>Clicking links in unsolicited email</td></tr><tr><td>Hover over links; check sender addresses</td><td>Trusting a name without checking the address</td></tr><tr><td>Protect your account with a strong password + MFA</td><td>Replying with any sensitive detail to an odd request</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">Your devices (endpoints)</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Do</th><th>Avoid</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Install updates promptly; keep antivirus on</td><td>Disabling or ignoring security alerts</td></tr><tr><td>Lock your screen every time you step away (Win+L)</td><td>Leaving devices unlocked and unattended</td></tr><tr><td>Use only approved software</td><td>Installing unauthorised apps; untrusted public Wi-Fi for work</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h2 class="section fade-up">Passwords &amp; MFA</h2><p class="fade-up">Use a <strong>unique</strong> password for every account &mdash; a password manager makes this effortless. Prefer a <strong>passphrase</strong>: a few random words like <em>correct-harbour-lantern-9</em> is both far stronger and easier to remember than <em>P@ss1!</em>. Add <strong>Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)</strong> everywhere you can.</p><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Why MFA is the single best habit</div><p>MFA asks for a second proof &mdash; a code or app approval &mdash; on top of your password. So even if an attacker steals or guesses your password, they still cannot get in. It defeats the most common attacks (phishing, reused passwords, credential stuffing) in one step. If you do one thing after this training, turn on MFA everywhere.</p></div><h2 class="section fade-up">Remote work, physical &amp; social</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>The habit</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Remote access</td><td>Company VPN + MFA; patched device; least access; disconnect idle sessions</td></tr><tr><td>Physical</td><td>No tailgating; escort visitors; clear desk; lock away sensitive papers; use your own badge</td></tr><tr><td>Social media</td><td>Do not post project names, screenshots or &lsquo;we work with X&rsquo;; attackers harvest this for spear phishing</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">If you remember nothing else &mdash; the four reflexes</div><p><strong>(1)</strong> Pause before you click. <strong>(2)</strong> Lock your screen. <strong>(3)</strong> Use unique passwords + MFA. <strong>(4)</strong> Report anything odd. Build those four into muscle memory and you have handled the large majority of real-world risk.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> Why is a four-word passphrase like &lsquo;correct-harbour-lantern-9&rsquo; both stronger and more usable than &lsquo;P@ss1!&rsquo;?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> It is far longer, which is what actually defeats password-cracking, yet it is memorable so you will not reuse or write it down. Short &lsquo;complex&rsquo; passwords are both weak and hard to remember &mdash; the worst of both worlds.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Email: do not open unexpected attachments or click unsolicited links; secure the account with MFA.</li><li>Devices: update, keep antivirus on, lock when you leave, only approved software.</li><li>Passwords: unique per account, prefer passphrases, and turn on MFA everywhere &mdash; MFA is the single best habit.</li><li>Remote/physical/social: VPN+MFA, no tailgating, clear desk, and do not leak project details online.</li><li>Four reflexes: pause-before-click, lock screen, unique passwords + MFA, report anything odd.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Best Practices &mdash; Email, Endpoint, Password, Remote slides 34&ndash;37</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m16">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Module 16</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Your Responsibilities<br>&amp; Acceptable Use</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The code of conduct every employee signs up to &mdash; and a one-question test for the grey areas.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>State your responsibilities under the Acceptable Use Policy and code of conduct, and apply the &lsquo;would this pass our audit?&rsquo; test to grey areas.</p></div><p class="fade-up">Security works because each of us owns our part. As a employee you agree to a simple code of conduct for how you use our systems and handle information.</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Responsibility</th><th>What it means</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Acceptable use</td><td>Use our organization systems and client assets only for authorised work tasks</td></tr><tr><td>Protect confidential information</td><td>Safeguard client and company data at all times</td></tr><tr><td>Follow security policies</td><td>Adhere to our organization and each client&#39;s security guidelines</td></tr><tr><td>Use systems responsibly</td><td>Access only what you are authorised to; act with care</td></tr><tr><td>Report and cooperate</td><td>Raise incidents promptly; cooperate with audits and investigations</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class="fade-up">None of this is meant to make work harder. It is the shared agreement that lets clients trust us with their most sensitive systems &mdash; which is, ultimately, what keeps our organization winning the work that pays all of us. Misuse can carry real consequences, up to disciplinary action, precisely because the stakes for clients are high.</p><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The grey-area test</div><p>Unsure whether something is allowed? Ask: <em>“Would I be comfortable if this appeared in our SOC&nbsp;2 audit, or if the client saw it?”</em> If yes, you are probably fine. If you hesitate, ask first. That single question resolves most judgement calls.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> You want to use a personal AI chatbot to summarise a confidential client document to save time. Apply the grey-area test.</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Would you be comfortable if the client or auditor saw you pasting their confidential data into an external tool? No &mdash; it sends their data outside our control (shadow IT). Use only approved tools, or ask first. The time saved is not worth the breach.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Use our organization systems and client assets only for authorised work.</li><li>Protect confidential data at all times and follow both our organization and client policies.</li><li>Report incidents promptly and cooperate with audits.</li><li>For any grey area, ask: would this be fine in our audit or in front of the client? If unsure, ask first.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Employee Responsibilities &amp; Code of Conduct slide 38</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m17">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Bonus</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">What Would<br>You Do?</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Six realistic scenarios to pressure-test everything you have learned &mdash; decide before you read the answer.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Apply everything from this handbook to realistic situations &mdash; the test of real learning.</p></div><p class="fade-up">Reading is one thing; reacting well under pressure is another. Work through these the way you would in real life &mdash; decide your answer before you read ours.</p><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario 1</div><p>A USB stick labelled &lsquo;Payroll 2026 &mdash; Confidential&rsquo; is on the floor near reception. You are curious whether it is genuinely sensitive.</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>Best response:</strong> Do not plug it in &mdash; this is classic <strong>baiting</strong>. Hand it to IT/security unopened. Plugging unknown USBs into a work machine can install malware instantly.</p></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario 2</div><p>You are working from a caf&eacute; and need to access a our organization system. The caf&eacute; Wi-Fi is open and free.</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>Best response:</strong> Do not use open Wi-Fi for work directly. Connect through the <strong>company VPN</strong> (with MFA) first, which encrypts your traffic. Better still, tether to your phone. Open networks let others snoop.</p></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario 3</div><p>A vendor emails an invoice that looks normal but says their bank account has &lsquo;recently changed &mdash; please pay to the new account.&rsquo;</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>Best response:</strong> Treat changed payment details as a major red flag for <strong>BEC/invoice fraud</strong>. Verify the change by calling the vendor on a number you already have (not one in the email) before any payment.</p></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario 4</div><p>A colleague is about to head to lunch and leaves their laptop unlocked with a client database open. They will &lsquo;only be ten minutes.&rsquo;</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>Best response:</strong> Politely remind them to lock it (Win+L) &mdash; an unlocked, unattended device is an open door to confidential data, and our clean-desk/lock-screen rule is a SOC&nbsp;2 control. Friendly nudges build the culture.</p></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Scenario 5</div><p>You receive a text: &lsquo;our organization IT: your account is suspended, re-activate here: [link].&rsquo; It looks urgent.</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>Best response:</strong> This is <strong>smishing</strong> (SMS phishing). Do not tap the link. Verify through the official IT channel. Urgency + a link + an account threat is the signature of a phish, on any medium.</p></div><div class="callout purple fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Knowledge check</div><p><strong>Q.</strong> What single instinct sits behind the right answer to every scenario above?</p><p style="margin-top:8px;"><strong>A.</strong> Pause and verify before acting &mdash; through a known, independent channel &mdash; and never let urgency, curiosity or convenience override that pause.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Real learning shows up as good reactions under pressure, not memorised definitions.</li><li>Stray USB = baiting; open Wi-Fi = VPN first; changed bank details = verify by phone.</li><li>Unlocked devices and smishing links are everyday traps &mdash; the fix is always pause-and-verify.</li><li>When in doubt, slow down and confirm through a channel you already trust.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: an out-of-the-box addition &mdash; applying the whole deck to real situations</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m18">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Reference Card</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Employee<br>Do&#39;s &amp; Don&#39;ts</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Your pocket reference, straight from our SOC 2 controls &mdash; what every employee must do, and must never do.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">This is your pocket reference &mdash; the practical do&#39;s and don&#39;ts every employee is expected to follow, drawn directly from our <strong>SOC&nbsp;2 compliance controls</strong>. Bookmark it. These rules are not optional: they protect you, your colleagues and our clients. If you are ever unsure, ask your manager <em>before</em> acting.</p><h2 class="section fade-up">01 &middot; Passwords &amp; Account Security</h2><div class="dd-grid fade-up"><div class="dd-col do"><div class="dd-head">&#10003; Do</div><ul><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10003;</span><div><strong>Use strong, unique passwords</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Min 8 chars, mixed; a passphrase is better; one per account</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10003;</span><div><strong>Change your password when prompted</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Do it immediately &mdash; do not postpone</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10003;</span><div><strong>Use only your own user ID</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Everyone logs in with their own unique credentials</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10003;</span><div><strong>Lock your screen when you step away</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Even for two minutes &mdash; Win+L</span></div></li></ul></div><div class="dd-col dont"><div class="dd-head">&#10007; Don&#39;t</div><ul><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10007;</span><div><strong>Never share your password</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Not with colleagues, not with IT, not with management &mdash; ever</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10007;</span><div><strong>Do not reuse or use weak passwords</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">No names, no sequences, nothing like password123</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10007;</span><div><strong>Do not log in with someone else&#39;s account</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Lockouts and incidents are logged</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10007;</span><div><strong>Do not leave sessions open unattended</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Log off manually; do not rely on timeout</span></div></li></ul></div></div><h2 class="section fade-up">02 &middot; Devices &amp; Data Handling</h2><div class="dd-grid fade-up"><div class="dd-col do"><div class="dd-head">&#10003; Do</div><ul><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10003;</span><div><strong>Use the VPN when working remotely</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">All remote access to our organization systems goes through the VPN</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10003;</span><div><strong>Keep antivirus active and updated</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Do not disable or ignore alerts</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10003;</span><div><strong>Shred printed sensitive documents</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Client data, internal reports, HR documents &mdash; into the shredder</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10003;</span><div><strong>Follow the Acceptable Use Policy</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">our organization systems are for work; personal use minimal</span></div></li></ul></div><div class="dd-col dont"><div class="dd-head">&#10007; Don&#39;t</div><ul><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10007;</span><div><strong>Never copy confidential data to USB/phone/external drives</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Removable media is restricted and monitored</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10007;</span><div><strong>Do not forward work files to personal email</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Keep them in approved systems and channels</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10007;</span><div><strong>Do not leave confidential documents on your desk</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Shred or lock away &mdash; clean desk</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10007;</span><div><strong>Do not install unauthorised software</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Get IT approval first</span></div></li></ul></div></div><h2 class="section fade-up">03 &middot; Physical Security &amp; Office Access</h2><div class="callout navy fade-up"><div class="callout-label">On-site discipline</div><p><strong>Restricted areas:</strong> never let anyone follow you in without their own access &mdash; report tailgating. <strong>Visitors:</strong> register at reception and escort them at all times. <strong>Surveillance:</strong> CCTV and access logs run 24/7; always use your own badge.</p></div><h2 class="section fade-up">04 &middot; Client Confidentiality</h2><div class="dd-grid fade-up"><div class="dd-col do"><div class="dd-head">&#10003; Do</div><ul><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10003;</span><div><strong>Treat all client data as strictly confidential</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Never discuss it in public or shared spaces</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10003;</span><div><strong>Handle client documents with care</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Follow retention rules; keep what is needed, dispose of the rest</span></div></li></ul></div><div class="dd-col dont"><div class="dd-head">&#10007; Don&#39;t</div><ul><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10007;</span><div><strong>Never disclose client data to third parties</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">NDA and confidentiality clauses apply</span></div></li><li><span class="dd-icon">&#10007;</span><div><strong>Do not share client information publicly or on social media</strong><br><span class="dd-sub">Including project names and screenshots</span></div></li></ul></div></div><div class="callout red fade-up"><div class="callout-label">If something feels wrong &mdash; report it</div><p>Suspicious email? Lost device? Clicked something you should not have? Door propped open, stranger unescorted? <strong>Report it to your manager or IT/security straight away.</strong> You will never be in trouble for reporting in good faith &mdash; silence is what turns a small issue into a serious breach. Security is everyone&#39;s job.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>These do&#39;s and don&#39;ts come straight from our organization&#39;s SOC 2 controls &mdash; requirements, not suggestions.</li><li>Passwords: strong, unique, private, your own ID, screen locked when away.</li><li>Data: VPN for remote work; no personal cloud/USB/email for confidential data; shred printed sensitive docs.</li><li>Physical: no tailgating, escort visitors, use your own badge. Client data is strictly confidential.</li><li>When anything feels wrong, report it immediately.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: Key Take-Away: Do&#39;s &amp; Don&#39;ts slide 39, plus our Employee Security Practices two-pager</p>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="infosec-m19">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Reference</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Glossary &amp;<br>Quick Reference</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Plain-English definitions for every term &mdash; plus the whole handbook distilled into a 60-second card.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What you will be able to do</div><p>Look up any term from this handbook in plain English, and keep the 60-second reference close.</p></div><h2 class="section fade-up">Glossary &mdash; plain English</h2><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Term</th><th>What it means</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>CIA Triad</td><td>Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability &mdash; the three goals of security</td></tr><tr><td>Phishing</td><td>Fake messages that trick you into giving up data or clicking malware</td></tr><tr><td>Social engineering</td><td>Manipulating people (not machines) to gain access or information</td></tr><tr><td>BEC</td><td>Business Email Compromise &mdash; impersonating a leader to request money/data</td></tr><tr><td>Malware</td><td>Malicious software (viruses, worms, trojans, ransomware, spyware)</td></tr><tr><td>Ransomware</td><td>Malware that encrypts your files and demands payment</td></tr><tr><td>MFA</td><td>Multi-Factor Authentication &mdash; a second proof beyond your password</td></tr><tr><td>VPN</td><td>Virtual Private Network &mdash; an encrypted tunnel for safe remote access</td></tr><tr><td>PII</td><td>Personally Identifiable Information &mdash; data that identifies a person</td></tr><tr><td>Phishing variants</td><td>Spear (targeted), Whaling (executives), Vishing (voice), Smishing (SMS)</td></tr><tr><td>Shadow IT</td><td>Using unapproved apps/services for work data</td></tr><tr><td>Least privilege</td><td>Giving the minimum access needed &mdash; nothing more</td></tr><tr><td>ISMS</td><td>Information Security Management System &mdash; how we manage security on purpose</td></tr><tr><td>SOC 2</td><td>An independent attestation that our security controls operate effectively</td></tr><tr><td>Incident</td><td>Any event that may compromise confidentiality, integrity or availability</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout gold fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The 60-second reference card</div><p><strong>Pause</strong> before every click. <strong>Verify</strong> unusual requests through a known channel. <strong>Lock</strong> your screen. <strong>Unique passwords + MFA</strong> everywhere. <strong>Keep work data in approved systems.</strong> <strong>Report</strong> anything odd immediately &mdash; you will never be in trouble for it. That is 90% of security in six habits.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Keep this glossary handy &mdash; plain-English definitions for every term in the handbook.</li><li>The 60-second card distils everything into six habits.</li><li>Security is mostly a small set of consistent behaviours, not technical wizardry.</li><li>When in doubt, pause, verify and report.</li></ol></div><p class="fade-up" style="font-family:var(--font-ui);font-size:10.5px;letter-spacing:.6px;color:var(--muted);text-transform:uppercase;border-top:1px dashed var(--border);padding-top:12px;margin-top:26px;">&#9670; Trainer note &mdash; reimagined from the consultant deck: an out-of-the-box addition &mdash; a trainer&#39;s glossary &amp; quick-reference</p>
 </div>
</section>

