<section class="chapter" id="iso27001-c1">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter One</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">What Is ISO 27001 &amp;<br>What Certification Means</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The global standard for managing information security &mdash; and how certification differs from a SOC 2 report.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up"><strong>ISO/IEC 27001:2022</strong> is the international standard for an <strong>Information Security Management System (ISMS)</strong> &mdash; a systematic, risk-based way to protect the confidentiality, integrity and availability of information. The :2022 edition refreshed the control set for modern realities like cloud and remote work.</p><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Certification vs the SOC 2 report</div><p>Both prove our security works, but differently. <strong>ISO 27001</strong> produces a <em>certificate</em> from an accredited body confirming our ISMS meets the standard &mdash; recognised globally. <strong>SOC 2</strong> produces a detailed <em>report</em>, written by auditors, describing how our controls were designed and operated over a period &mdash; popular with North-American clients. our organization pursues both because different clients ask for different proof.</p></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The meaning of the certificate</div><p>The certificate tells a client: an independent body examined how our organization identifies information risks and manages them with proportionate controls, and confirmed it meets a rigorous global standard. It is risk-based, not a fixed checklist &mdash; which is why it adapts to our actual threats rather than a generic list.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>ISO/IEC 27001:2022 is the global standard for an Information Security Management System.</li><li>It is risk-based: find your information risks, apply proportionate controls.</li><li>Certification = an accredited body issues a globally recognised certificate.</li><li>ISO 27001 gives a certificate; SOC 2 gives a report &mdash; our organization maintains both.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso27001-c2">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Two</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">How the Standard Is Built &mdash;<br>Clauses 4&ndash;10 + Annex A</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The management system plus the catalogue of 93 controls.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">ISO 27001 has two halves. First, the <strong>management-system clauses (4&ndash;10)</strong> &mdash; the machinery that keeps security managed, not accidental. Second, <strong>Annex A</strong> &mdash; a catalogue of controls you select from based on your risks.</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Clause</th><th>Requirement</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>4</td><td>Context &mdash; interested parties and ISMS scope</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Leadership &mdash; policy, roles, top-management commitment</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Planning &mdash; risk assessment, risk treatment, objectives</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>Support &mdash; resources, competence, awareness, documented information</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>Operation &mdash; run the risk assessment and treatment</td></tr><tr><td>9</td><td>Performance evaluation &mdash; monitoring, internal audit, management review</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>Improvement &mdash; nonconformity and continual improvement</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Annex A 2022 &mdash; 93 controls, 4 themes</div><p>The 2022 edition reorganised Annex A into <strong>93 controls</strong> across four themes: <strong>Organizational</strong> (policies, supplier security, threat intelligence), <strong>People</strong> (screening, awareness, responsibilities), <strong>Physical</strong> (secure areas, equipment, clear desk) and <strong>Technological</strong> (access control, encryption, logging, secure development). It added 11 new controls for modern risks such as cloud services, data leakage prevention and threat intelligence.</p></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The Statement of Applicability (SoA)</div><p>You do not implement all 93 blindly. You assess risk, then select and justify the controls that address it in the <strong>Statement of Applicability</strong> &mdash; the bridge between your risk assessment and your controls, and one of the most important documents an auditor reads.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Two halves: management-system clauses (4&ndash;10) plus Annex A controls.</li><li>Annex A 2022 has 93 controls in four themes: Organizational, People, Physical, Technological.</li><li>Controls are chosen by risk and justified in the Statement of Applicability (SoA).</li><li>The clauses keep security continuously managed; Annex A is the control toolbox.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso27001-c3">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Three</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Building the ISMS &mdash;<br>The Road to Compliance</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Step by step, what it takes to meet ISO 27001.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">Everything in ISO 27001 flows from <strong>risk</strong>. Building a compliant ISMS follows a clear sequence:</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>What the organisation must do</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1. Define scope &amp; context</td><td>Decide what the ISMS covers; identify interested parties</td></tr><tr><td>2. Leadership &amp; policy</td><td>Top management commits; an information security policy is set</td></tr><tr><td>3. Risk assessment</td><td>Identify assets, threats and vulnerabilities; rate likelihood and impact</td></tr><tr><td>4. Risk treatment</td><td>For each risk: treat, tolerate, transfer or terminate</td></tr><tr><td>5. Select controls &amp; write the SoA</td><td>Choose Annex A controls that address the risks; justify inclusions/exclusions</td></tr><tr><td>6. Implement controls</td><td>Put the chosen technical and organisational controls in place</td></tr><tr><td>7. Train &amp; raise awareness</td><td>Security awareness for all staff (this very training)</td></tr><tr><td>8. Operate &amp; record</td><td>Run the ISMS and capture evidence</td></tr><tr><td>9. Internal audit &amp; management review</td><td>Check the ISMS works; leadership reviews it</td></tr><tr><td>10. Certification audit</td><td>Accredited body runs Stage 1 and Stage 2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The four ways to treat a risk</div><p><strong>Treat</strong> (apply a control), <strong>Tolerate</strong> (accept if low enough), <strong>Transfer</strong> (share via insurance or a vendor), or <strong>Terminate</strong> (stop the risky activity). Each decision is recorded and signed off &mdash; that record is core audit evidence.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>The ISMS is driven by a documented information-security risk assessment.</li><li>Each risk is treated, tolerated, transferred or terminated &mdash; and recorded.</li><li>Selected controls are justified in the Statement of Applicability.</li><li>Awareness training, operation, internal audit and management review complete the system.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso27001-c4">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Four</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">The Compliance Officer&#39;s<br>Documentation Vault</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The documents and records ISO 27001 expects you to maintain and produce on demand.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">ISO 27001 names specific &lsquo;documented information&rsquo; that must exist. A compliance officer keeps these current, controlled and ready for the auditor.</p><h3 class="sub fade-up">Mandatory documents</h3><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Document</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>ISMS scope</td><td>What the ISMS covers</td></tr><tr><td>Information security policy &amp; objectives</td><td>Direction and measurable targets</td></tr><tr><td>Risk assessment &amp; risk treatment methodology</td><td>How risks are identified and handled</td></tr><tr><td>Statement of Applicability (SoA)</td><td>Which controls apply and why</td></tr><tr><td>Risk treatment plan</td><td>How each risk will be addressed</td></tr><tr><td>Key control procedures</td><td>Access control, asset management, secure development, etc.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3 class="sub fade-up">Mandatory records (evidence)</h3><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Record</th><th>What it proves</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Risk assessment results</td><td>Risks were identified and rated</td></tr><tr><td>Competence &amp; awareness records</td><td>Staff are trained (e.g. this course&#39;s completion log)</td></tr><tr><td>Monitoring &amp; measurement results</td><td>Controls are tracked for effectiveness</td></tr><tr><td>Internal audit programme &amp; reports</td><td>The ISMS is independently checked</td></tr><tr><td>Management review minutes</td><td>Leadership reviews and steers security</td></tr><tr><td>Nonconformity &amp; corrective-action records</td><td>Issues are logged and resolved</td></tr><tr><td>Incident records</td><td>Security incidents are captured and handled</td></tr><tr><td>Access logs / user access reviews</td><td>Access is controlled and periodically reviewed</td></tr><tr><td>Supplier / third-party security records</td><td>Vendor risk is managed</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout navy fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The compliance officer&#39;s rhythm</div><p>Beyond holding documents, the officer runs the cadence: schedule and track the risk reviews, the internal audit programme, the access reviews, the management reviews and the corrective actions &mdash; and keep dated evidence of each. An auditor will ask &lsquo;show me the last access review&rsquo; and expect a record with a date and an owner.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Mandatory documents include scope, policy, risk methodology, SoA, risk treatment plan and key procedures.</li><li>Mandatory records include risk results, training, monitoring, internal audits, management reviews, incidents and access reviews.</li><li>The training-completion log for this very course is audit evidence.</li><li>The officer keeps a cadence of reviews with dated, owned evidence for each.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso27001-c5">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Five</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">How the<br>Audit Works</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The certification journey, surveillance, and how findings are managed.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">An accredited certification body runs the audits. The cycle mirrors other ISO standards.</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>What happens</th><th>What the auditor checks</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Application &amp; selection</td><td>You engage an accredited certification body</td><td>Scope of certification is agreed</td></tr><tr><td>Stage 1 audit (readiness)</td><td>Documentation review, on-site readiness check</td><td>Are the management system documents in place and complete?</td></tr><tr><td>Stage 2 audit (certification)</td><td>In-depth, on-site assessment of how it operates</td><td>Is the system actually implemented, used and effective? Evidence sampled.</td></tr><tr><td>Certification decision</td><td>Body reviews findings and issues the certificate</td><td>Major nonconformities must be closed first</td></tr><tr><td>Surveillance audits</td><td>Usually annual, lighter-touch</td><td>Is the system still operating and improving?</td></tr><tr><td>Recertification</td><td>Every 3 years, full reassessment</td><td>Renews the certificate for another cycle</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout navy fade-up"><div class="callout-label">How findings work</div><p>Auditors raise <strong>nonconformities</strong> when a requirement is not met. A <strong>major</strong> nonconformity (a whole requirement missing, or a systemic failure) blocks or suspends certification until fixed. A <strong>minor</strong> nonconformity (an isolated lapse) requires a corrective-action plan. <strong>Observations / opportunities for improvement</strong> are advisory. For every finding the compliance officer logs the issue, root cause, correction, and evidence it was fixed &mdash; that record is itself audited next time.</p></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What auditors probe in security specifically</div><p>Expect questions on: how risks are assessed and treated; whether access is least-privilege and reviewed; how incidents are detected and handled; whether staff are trained and aware (they will ask <em>you</em>); and whether suppliers are managed. They sample real evidence &mdash; logs, tickets, reviews &mdash; not just policies.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Stage 1 (documentation/readiness) then Stage 2 (implementation) lead to certification.</li><li>Annual surveillance audits and a 3-yearly recertification keep it alive.</li><li>Majors block certification; minors need corrective actions; observations are advisory.</li><li>Auditors sample real evidence and talk to ordinary staff &mdash; awareness is part of the test.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso27001-c6">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Six</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">The Controls &amp;<br>Processes It Incorporates</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The Annex A themes and the operational security processes a 27001 ISMS runs.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">Annex A&#39;s four themes translate into living processes the organisation runs continuously:</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>Representative controls / processes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Organizational</td><td>Policies, supplier &amp; cloud security, threat intelligence, incident management</td></tr><tr><td>People</td><td>Background screening, security awareness training, defined responsibilities, joiner/mover/leaver</td></tr><tr><td>Physical</td><td>Secure areas, clear desk/clear screen, equipment security, secure disposal</td></tr><tr><td>Technological</td><td>Access control &amp; MFA, encryption, logging &amp; monitoring, secure development, backup, malware protection, vulnerability &amp; patch management</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The processes that keep it running</div><p>Day to day, the ISMS runs: risk management, access management (with periodic access reviews), incident management, change management, vulnerability and patch management, business continuity, supplier management, and security awareness. Each leaves records &mdash; which are exactly what the audit samples.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Annex A 2022 themes: Organizational, People, Physical, Technological.</li><li>These become living processes: access, incident, change, vulnerability, continuity, supplier management.</li><li>Human behaviour (awareness, clear desk, MFA) is a primary control, not an afterthought.</li><li>Every process produces records that become audit evidence.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso27001-c7">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Seven</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Maintaining Certification<br>&amp; Your Role</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">How our organization keeps the certificate &mdash; and how the same controls serve SOC 2.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">Certification is kept by living the ISMS between audits. The bulk of that is the everyday security behaviour taught throughout the Information Security handbook on the home page.</p><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">How you help keep certification</div><p>Follow the security policies and the employee do&#39;s and don&#39;ts; complete this awareness training; report incidents and suspicious activity promptly; handle classified information correctly; and cooperate when auditors ask to see how a control works. Auditors love talking to ordinary staff &mdash; your good habits are the evidence.</p></div><div class="callout navy fade-up"><div class="callout-label">One ISMS, two proofs</div><p>The same ISMS that earns ISO 27001 underpins our SOC 2 attestation. When you follow a security control you support both at once. Do it once, satisfy both.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Certification is kept by living the ISMS, verified at annual surveillance audits.</li><li>Your part: follow policies, finish training, report incidents, handle data correctly, cooperate with audits.</li><li>The same controls support both ISO 27001 and SOC 2.</li><li>Ordinary staff habits are exactly what auditors sample.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso27001-c8">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Quick Reference</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">ISO 27001 vs SOC 2<br>at a Glance</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">A side-by-side to settle which is which.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th></th><th>ISO/IEC 27001:2022</th><th>SOC 2</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>What it is</td><td>A certifiable international standard for an ISMS</td><td>An attestation report on control effectiveness</td></tr><tr><td>Deliverable</td><td>A certificate from an accredited body</td><td>A detailed report from a CPA/audit firm</td></tr><tr><td>Basis</td><td>Risk-based ISMS + Annex A controls</td><td>Trust Services Criteria (Security, etc.)</td></tr><tr><td>Recognition</td><td>Global</td><td>Strong in North America</td></tr><tr><td>Cycle</td><td>3-year cycle, annual surveillance</td><td>Type II covers a period (e.g. 6&ndash;12 months)</td></tr><tr><td>Shared foundation</td><td>Same controls, same evidence &mdash; one ISMS serves both</td><td></td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The bottom line</div><p>They are not competitors; they are two lenses on the same security system. our organization maintains both so we can hand any client the proof they prefer.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>ISO 27001 = certificate against a global standard; SOC 2 = report on control effectiveness.</li><li>Both rest on the same underlying ISMS and controls.</li><li>ISO 27001 runs a 3-year cycle; SOC 2 Type II covers a defined period.</li><li>our organization keeps both to satisfy every client&#39;s preferred form of proof.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>

 </div>
</div>

