<section class="chapter" id="iso20000-c1">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter One</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">What Is ISO 20000-1 &amp;<br>What Certification Means</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The international standard for IT service management &mdash; running IT services like a disciplined business.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up"><strong>ISO/IEC 20000-1:2018</strong> is the international standard for an <strong>IT Service Management System (SMS)</strong>. Where ISO 9001 is about quality in general and ISO 27001 is about security, ISO 20000-1 is specifically about <strong>delivering and supporting IT services reliably</strong> &mdash; the discipline behind help desks, change control, uptime commitments and continual service improvement.</p><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What certification means here</div><p>Certification confirms an accredited body verified that our organization manages its IT services to a professional, repeatable standard &mdash; incidents, changes and service levels are handled deliberately, not reactively. For clients who depend on us to keep systems running, it is concrete proof of operational maturity, and it is increasingly requested in operations-and-maintenance and managed-service contracts.</p></div><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">ISO 20000-1 and ITIL</div><p>You may have heard of <strong>ITIL</strong> &mdash; a popular set of IT-service best practices. ITIL is guidance you can adopt; ISO 20000-1 is the <strong>certifiable standard</strong> you can be audited against. ITIL gives the how-to; ISO 20000-1 gives the formal requirements. They fit together naturally.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>ISO/IEC 20000-1:2018 is the standard for an IT Service Management System (SMS).</li><li>It is about reliably delivering and supporting IT services.</li><li>Certification = an accredited body verified our service management is professional and repeatable.</li><li>ITIL is the best-practice guidance; ISO 20000-1 is the certifiable standard.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso20000-c2">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Two</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">How the Standard<br>Is Built</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The management-system backbone plus the service management processes.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">Like its sisters, ISO 20000-1 uses the ten-clause High-Level Structure and the <strong>Plan-Do-Check-Act</strong> cycle: leadership, planning, support, operation, evaluation and improvement. On that backbone sit the <strong>service management processes</strong> that make it distinctive.</p><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The service management processes</div><p><strong>Service level management</strong> (SLAs) &middot; <strong>Service catalogue management</strong> &middot; <strong>Incident</strong> &amp; <strong>service request</strong> management &middot; <strong>Problem management</strong> &middot; <strong>Change management</strong> &middot; <strong>Release &amp; deployment</strong> &middot; <strong>Configuration management</strong> (the CMDB) &middot; <strong>Capacity</strong> &amp; <strong>availability</strong> management &middot; <strong>Service continuity</strong> &middot; <strong>Supplier management</strong> &middot; <strong>Budgeting &amp; accounting</strong> for services.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>The SMS uses the same ten-clause, PDCA backbone as 9001 and 27001.</li><li>On top sit the service management processes that define the standard.</li><li>Key processes: service level, incident, problem, change, release, configuration, capacity, availability, continuity, supplier.</li><li>Together they turn IT support into a managed, measured service.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso20000-c3">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Three</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Establishing the SMS &mdash;<br>The Road to Compliance</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">What an organisation must do to meet ISO 20000-1.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">Becoming compliant means standing up a real service management system:</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>What the organisation must do</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1. Define scope &amp; services</td><td>Decide which services and which the SMS covers</td></tr><tr><td>2. Leadership &amp; service policy</td><td>Top management commits; a service management policy and objectives are set</td></tr><tr><td>3. Build the service catalogue &amp; SLAs</td><td>Define services and the agreed service levels</td></tr><tr><td>4. Stand up the core processes</td><td>Incident, problem, change, configuration, release, etc.</td></tr><tr><td>5. Establish the CMDB</td><td>Know the assets and configuration items you run</td></tr><tr><td>6. Plan capacity, availability &amp; continuity</td><td>Ensure services can meet demand and recover from disruption</td></tr><tr><td>7. Manage suppliers</td><td>Control external providers that support the services</td></tr><tr><td>8. Operate &amp; record</td><td>Run the processes and capture evidence (tickets, approvals, reports)</td></tr><tr><td>9. Measure, internally audit, review</td><td>Track SLAs; audit the SMS; management review</td></tr><tr><td>10. Certification audit</td><td>Accredited body runs Stage 1 and Stage 2</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">The heart of it</div><p>If you can show that incidents are restored against SLA, changes go through review with rollback plans, and problems are root-caused so they stop recurring &mdash; with records for each &mdash; you are most of the way to compliant.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Define scope and services, secure leadership, build the catalogue and SLAs.</li><li>Stand up the core processes and a CMDB; plan capacity, availability and continuity.</li><li>Manage suppliers, operate with records, then measure, audit and review.</li><li>An accredited body then audits in two stages to certify.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso20000-c4">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Four</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">The Compliance Officer&#39;s<br>Documentation Vault</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The records that prove the service runs the way you say it does.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">Service management generates a lot of operational evidence. The compliance officer keeps the documents current and ensures the day-to-day records are captured in the service tools.</p><h3 class="sub fade-up">Documents to maintain</h3><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Document</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>SMS scope</td><td>Which services and units are covered</td></tr><tr><td>Service management policy &amp; objectives</td><td>Direction and measurable targets</td></tr><tr><td>Service catalogue</td><td>The services offered and their characteristics</td></tr><tr><td>SLAs (service level agreements)</td><td>The agreed targets per service</td></tr><tr><td>Process procedures</td><td>How incident, problem, change, etc. are run</td></tr><tr><td>Service continuity &amp; availability plans</td><td>How services stay up and recover</td></tr></tbody></table></div><h3 class="sub fade-up">Records to retain</h3><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Record</th><th>What it proves</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Incident &amp; service request records</td><td>Issues are logged and restored against SLA</td></tr><tr><td>Problem records &amp; known errors</td><td>Root causes are found and removed</td></tr><tr><td>Change records &amp; approvals</td><td>Changes are reviewed, approved and have rollback plans</td></tr><tr><td>Release &amp; deployment records</td><td>Releases are controlled</td></tr><tr><td>Configuration records (CMDB)</td><td>Assets and their relationships are known</td></tr><tr><td>SLA performance reports</td><td>Service levels are measured and met</td></tr><tr><td>Capacity &amp; availability reports</td><td>Services can meet demand and uptime targets</td></tr><tr><td>Internal audit, management review, corrective actions</td><td>The SMS is checked, steered and improved</td></tr><tr><td>Supplier performance records</td><td>External providers are managed</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout navy fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Where the records live</div><p>Most of these are captured automatically in the service desk / ITSM tool as tickets, approvals and reports. The compliance officer&#39;s job is to ensure the processes are configured so the evidence is created as a by-product of doing the work &mdash; and that SLA and audit reports are produced and reviewed on a schedule.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Maintain SMS scope, service policy/objectives, service catalogue, SLAs, procedures and continuity plans.</li><li>Retain records for incident, problem, change, release, configuration (CMDB) and SLA performance.</li><li>Also keep capacity/availability reports, internal audits, management reviews and supplier performance.</li><li>Configure the ITSM tool so evidence is generated automatically by doing the work.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso20000-c5">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Five</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">How the<br>Audit Works</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The certification journey for the SMS.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">The audit cycle is the same family as the other ISO standards, run by an accredited certification body.</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>What happens</th><th>What the auditor checks</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Application &amp; selection</td><td>You engage an accredited certification body</td><td>Scope of certification is agreed</td></tr><tr><td>Stage 1 audit (readiness)</td><td>Documentation review, on-site readiness check</td><td>Are the management system documents in place and complete?</td></tr><tr><td>Stage 2 audit (certification)</td><td>In-depth, on-site assessment of how it operates</td><td>Is the system actually implemented, used and effective? Evidence sampled.</td></tr><tr><td>Certification decision</td><td>Body reviews findings and issues the certificate</td><td>Major nonconformities must be closed first</td></tr><tr><td>Surveillance audits</td><td>Usually annual, lighter-touch</td><td>Is the system still operating and improving?</td></tr><tr><td>Recertification</td><td>Every 3 years, full reassessment</td><td>Renews the certificate for another cycle</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="callout navy fade-up"><div class="callout-label">How findings work</div><p>Auditors raise <strong>nonconformities</strong> when a requirement is not met. A <strong>major</strong> nonconformity (a whole requirement missing, or a systemic failure) blocks or suspends certification until fixed. A <strong>minor</strong> nonconformity (an isolated lapse) requires a corrective-action plan. <strong>Observations / opportunities for improvement</strong> are advisory. For every finding the compliance officer logs the issue, root cause, correction, and evidence it was fixed &mdash; that record is itself audited next time.</p></div><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">What auditors probe in service management</div><p>Expect them to trace real tickets: pick an incident and check it was logged, prioritised and resolved against SLA; pick a change and check it was reviewed, approved and had a rollback plan; pick a recurring issue and check problem management addressed the root cause. They also check SLA reports, the CMDB&#39;s accuracy and continuity tests.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Stage 1 then Stage 2 lead to certification; annual surveillance and 3-yearly recertification keep it.</li><li>Majors block certification; minors need corrective actions.</li><li>Auditors trace real incidents, changes and problems end-to-end.</li><li>Accurate SLA reports, a reliable CMDB and tested continuity plans are key evidence.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso20000-c6">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Six</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">The Service Processes &mdash;<br>Incident, Problem &amp; Change</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">The processes that do the heavy lifting, demystified.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">Three processes are confused most often &mdash; getting them straight is most of service management.</p><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Process</th><th>Goal</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Incident</strong></td><td>Restore service fast</td><td>The portal is down &mdash; get it back up now</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Problem</strong></td><td>Remove the root cause so it stops recurring</td><td>Why did it go down, and how do we prevent it?</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Change</strong></td><td>Make modifications safely, with review and rollback</td><td>Deploy the fix through a controlled release</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class="fade-up">A worked example ties them together: a server crashes (<em>incident</em>) &rarr; you restart it to restore service &rarr; investigation finds a memory leak (<em>problem</em>) &rarr; you deploy a patch through a controlled release (<em>change</em>). Keeping these distinct is what stops the same outage every week.</p><div class="callout blue fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Why controlled change pays off</div><p>Most major outages trace back to an unmanaged change. A quick review and a rollback plan are cheap insurance against an expensive weekend &mdash; which is exactly why change management is a headline process in the standard.</p></div><div class="table-wrap fade-up"><table><thead><tr><th>Other key processes</th><th>What it ensures</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Service level management</td><td>Targets are agreed and tracked</td></tr><tr><td>Configuration management (CMDB)</td><td>You know what you run and how it connects</td></tr><tr><td>Capacity &amp; availability</td><td>Services meet demand and uptime commitments</td></tr><tr><td>Service continuity</td><td>You can recover from major disruption</td></tr><tr><td>Supplier management</td><td>External providers meet their commitments</td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>Incident = restore fast; Problem = remove the root cause; Change = modify safely with rollback.</li><li>They flow together: fix now, prevent recurrence, deploy the fix under control.</li><li>Most major outages come from unmanaged change &mdash; review and rollback prevent them.</li><li>Service level, configuration (CMDB), capacity, continuity and supplier management round out the system.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>
<section class="chapter" id="iso20000-c7">
 <div class="chapter-header fade-up">
 <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chapter Seven</div>
 <h1 class="chapter-title">Maintaining Certification<br>&amp; Your Role</h1>
 <p class="chapter-intro">Keeping the SMS alive, and how it relates to ITIL and our other standards.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="content-body">
<p class="fade-up">If you work in operations, support, or on any system our organization keeps running for a client, ISO 20000-1 is the rulebook behind your tickets, SLAs and change windows. Keeping certification means living those processes.</p><div class="callout teal fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Your part in good service management</div><p>Log incidents properly so patterns can be seen; never make undocumented changes to live systems; follow the change process even when it feels slow; and feed recurring issues into problem management instead of re-fixing them each time. Good records are what let our organization honour SLAs &mdash; and prove it.</p></div><div class="callout navy fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Three standards, one way of working</div><p>ISO 9001 (quality), ISO 27001 (security) and ISO 20000-1 (service) share the same PDCA spine and reward the same behaviour: define the process, follow it, record it, improve it. Master that habit once and you support all three certifications at the same time.</p></div><div class="takeaway fade-up"><div class="callout-label">Key Takeaways</div><ol><li>ISO 20000-1 is the rulebook behind tickets, SLAs and change windows.</li><li>Your part: log incidents, avoid undocumented changes, follow change control, escalate recurring problems.</li><li>Records are what let our organization honour and prove its service commitments.</li><li>All three ISO standards share PDCA &mdash; one good habit supports them all.</li></ol></div>
 </div>
</section>

 </div>
</div>

